{"title_page": "Miguel Falc\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{spanish name 2|Falc\u00f3n|Garc\u00eda-Ramos}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Miguel Falc\u00f3n\n| image = \n| fullname = Miguel Falc\u00f3n Garc\u00eda-Ramos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|4|24|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Toledo, Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.83}}\n| position = [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132000\n| years2 = 1999\u20132001\n| years3 = 2001\u20132002\n| years4 = 2002\u20132003 \n| years5 = 2003\u20132007 \n| years6 = 2007\u20132008\n| years7 = 2008\u20132010\n| years8 = 2010\u20132012\n| years9 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid C]]\n| clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B]] \n| clubs3 = [[M\u00e9rida UD|M\u00e9rida]]\n| clubs4 = [[CD Legan\u00e9s|Legan\u00e9s]]\n| clubs5 = [[Ciudad de Murcia|Ciudad Murcia]]\n| clubs6 = [[Granada 74 CF|Granada 74]]\n| clubs7 = [[FC Cartagena|Cartagena]]\n| clubs8 = [[Real Oviedo|Oviedo]]\n| clubs9 = [[CD Toledo|Toledo]]\n| caps1 =\n| caps2 = 25\n| caps3 = 29\n| caps4 = 9  \n| caps5 = 124\n| caps6 = 30  \n| caps7 = 55\n| caps8 = 35\n| caps9 = 25\n| totalcaps = 332\n| goals1 =  \n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 2\n| goals4 = 1  \n| goals5 = 6\n| goals6 = 0 \n| goals7 = 0\n| goals8 = 0\n| goals9 = 0\n| totalgoals = 9\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 2014\u20132018\n| manageryears2 = 2018\n| managerclubs1 = [[CD Toledo|Toledo]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs2 = [[CD Toledo|Toledo]]\n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Miguel Falc\u00f3n Garc\u00eda-Ramos''' (born 24 April 1979) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], and a current [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nHe amassed [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] totals of 185 games and six goals over eight seasons, in representation of five clubs.\n\n==Playing career==\nFalc\u00f3n was born in [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]], [[Castile-La Mancha]]. After rough starts in [[Madrid]], only appearing for [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|Atl\u00e9tico]]'s [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|B]] and [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid C|C-teams]], he joined another club in the city, [[CD Legan\u00e9s]], but appeared very rarely during a sole [[2002\u201303 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division season]]. Subsequently, staying in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|that level]], he stabilised his career, going on to spend five campaigns with [[Ciudad de Murcia]] \u2013 they were renamed [[Granada 74 CF]] for [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2007\u201308]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/2a_division/granada_74/es/desarrollo/1012881.html|title=Jaime y Falc\u00f3n fichan por el Granada 74|trans-title=Jaime and Falc\u00f3n sign for Granada 74|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=4 July 2007|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Granada's 2008 relegation, Falc\u00f3n signed with [[FC Cartagena]] of [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|division three]], helping them promote in [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his first year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2009/05/24/futbol/mas_futbol/1243197248.html|title=Cartagena vuelve a Segunda 22 a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s|trans-title=Cartagena return to ''Segunda'' 22 years later|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> He contributed with 29 league games [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]], as the [[Region of Murcia|Murcia]] side overachieved for a final fifth place.\n\nIn July 2010, aged 31, Falc\u00f3n returned to the third tier after moving to [[Real Oviedo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lne.es/deportes/2010/07/13/miguel-falcon-cierra-fichaje-oviedo/941807.html|title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n cierra su fichaje por el Oviedo|trans-title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n completes his transfer to Oviedo|newspaper=[[La Nueva Espa\u00f1a]]|first=Elena|last=Casero|language=Spanish|date=13 July 2010|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> Two years later, he signed for his hometown club [[CD Toledo]] in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/espana/castilla-la-mancha/toledo/abci-toledo-firma-centrocampista-miguel-201207200000_noticia.html|title=El Toledo firma al centrocampista Miguel Falc\u00f3n|trans-title=Toledo sign midfielder Miguel Falc\u00f3n|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=20 July 2012|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Coaching career==\nFalc\u00f3n retired at the end of the [[2012\u201313 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2012\u201313 season]] \u2013 in which Toledo won promotion \u2013 and became assistant manager. When [[On\u00e9simo S\u00e1nchez]] was dismissed in January 2018, he was named head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encastillalamancha.es/castilla-la-mancha/miguel-falcon-segundo-de-onesimo-nuevo-entrenador-del-cd-toledo/|title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n, segundo de On\u00e9simo, nuevo entrenador del CD Toledo|trans-title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n, On\u00e9simo's assistant, new manager of CD Toledo|publisher=En Castilla La Mancha|language=Spanish|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> In June, after being [[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|unable to prevent relegation]], he was given a job in the club's academy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/espana/castilla-la-mancha/toledo/deportes/abci-fran-cano-nuevo-entrenador-toledo-201806071147_noticia.html|title=El Toledo elige a Fran Cano para devolver al equipo a Segunda B|trans-title=Toledo choose Fran Cano as the man to return the team to ''Segunda B''|newspaper=ABC|first=B.|last=Cervantes|language=Spanish|date=7 June 2018|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|24 March 2018}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\t\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\t\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[CD Toledo|Toledo]]\n|{{Flagicon|Spain}}\t\n|align=left|24 January 2018\t\n|aligb=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|9|4|2|3|for=9|against=8|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l4629.html?temp=2017-18|title=Falc\u00f3n: Miguel Falc\u00f3n Garc\u00eda-Ramos|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref>\t\t\n|-\t\t\n| colspan=4 | '''Career Total'''\n{{WDLtot|9|4|2|3|for=9|against=8|diff=yes}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|4629}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|4629}}\n\n{{CD Toledo managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Falcon, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Toledo, Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Castilian-Manchegan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid C players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B players]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9rida UD footballers]]\n[[Category:CD Legan\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:Ciudad de Murcia footballers]]\n[[Category:Granada 74 CF footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Cartagena footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo players]]\n[[Category:CD Toledo players]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:CD Toledo managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name 2|Falc\u00f3n|Garc\u00eda-Ramos}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Miguel Falc\u00f3n\n| image = \n| fullname = Miguel Falc\u00f3n Garc\u00eda-Ramos\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|4|24|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Toledo, Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.83}}\n| position = [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132000\n| years2 = 1999\u20132001\n| years3 = 2001\u20132002\n| years4 = 2002\u20132003 \n| years5 = 2003\u20132007 \n| years6 = 2007\u20132008\n| years7 = 2008\u20132010\n| years8 = 2010\u20132012\n| years9 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid C|Atl\u00e9tico C]]\n| clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|Atl\u00e9tico B]] \n| clubs3 = [[M\u00e9rida UD|M\u00e9rida]]\n| clubs4 = [[CD Legan\u00e9s|Legan\u00e9s]]\n| clubs5 = [[Ciudad de Murcia|Ciudad Murcia]]\n| clubs6 = [[Granada 74 CF|Granada 74]]\n| clubs7 = [[FC Cartagena|Cartagena]]\n| clubs8 = [[Real Oviedo|Oviedo]]\n| clubs9 = [[CD Toledo|Toledo]]\n| caps1 =\n| caps2 = 25\n| caps3 = 29\n| caps4 = 9  \n| caps5 = 124\n| caps6 = 30  \n| caps7 = 55\n| caps8 = 35\n| caps9 = 25\n| totalcaps = 332\n| goals1 =  \n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 2\n| goals4 = 1  \n| goals5 = 6\n| goals6 = 0 \n| goals7 = 0\n| goals8 = 0\n| goals9 = 0\n| totalgoals = 9\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 2014\u20132018\n| manageryears2 = 2018\n| managerclubs1 = [[CD Toledo|Toledo]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs2 = [[CD Toledo|Toledo]]\n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Miguel Falc\u00f3n Garc\u00eda-Ramos''' (born 24 April 1979) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], and is a current manager.\n\nHe amassed [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] totals of 185 games and six goals during eight seasons, in representation of five clubs.\n\n==Football career==\nFalc\u00f3n was born in [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]], [[Castile-La Mancha]]. After rough starts in [[Madrid]], only appearing for [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid|Atl\u00e9tico]]'s [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|B]] and [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid C|C-teams]], he joined another club in the city, [[CD Legan\u00e9s]], but appeared very rarely during a sole [[2002\u201303 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division season]]. Subsequently, staying in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|that level]], he stabilized his career, going on to spend five campaigns with [[Ciudad de Murcia]] \u2013 they were renamed [[Granada 74 CF]] for [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2007\u201308]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/2a_division/granada_74/es/desarrollo/1012881.html|title=Jaime y Falc\u00f3n fichan por el Granada 74|trans-title=Jaime and Falc\u00f3n sign for Granada 74|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=4 July 2007|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Granada's 2008 relegation, Falc\u00f3n signed with [[FC Cartagena]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|division three]], helping it promote in [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his first year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2009/05/24/futbol/mas_futbol/1243197248.html|title=Cartagena vuelve a Segunda 22 a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s|trans-title=Cartagena return to ''Segunda'' 22 years later|newspaper=Marca|language=es|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> He contributed with 29 league games in [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]], as the [[Region of Murcia|Murcia]] side overachieved for a final fifth place.\n\nIn July 2010, aged 31, Falc\u00f3n returned to the third tier after moving to [[Real Oviedo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n cierra su fichaje por el Oviedo|trans-title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n completes his transfer to Oviedo |url=https://www.lne.es/deportes/2010/07/13/miguel-falcon-cierra-fichaje-oviedo/941807.html |accessdate=17 November 2019 |work=[[La Nueva Espa\u00f1a]] |date=13 July 2010 |language=Spanish}}</ref> Two years later, he signed for his hometown club [[CD Toledo]] in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news |title=El Toledo firma al centrocampista Miguel Falc\u00f3n|trans-title=Toledo sign midfielder Miguel Falc\u00f3n |url=https://www.abc.es/espana/castilla-la-mancha/toledo/abci-toledo-firma-centrocampista-miguel-201207200000_noticia.html |accessdate=17 November 2019 |work=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]] |date=20 July 2012 |language=Spanish}}</ref> He retired after [[2012\u201313 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|one season]] \u2013 in which they won promotion \u2013 and became assistant manager; when [[On\u00e9simo S\u00e1nchez]] was dismissed in January 2018, he became head coach.<ref>{{cite news |title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n, segundo de On\u00e9simo, nuevo entrenador del CD Toledo|trans-title=Miguel Falc\u00f3n, On\u00e9simo's assistant, new manager of CD Toledo |url=http://www.encastillalamancha.es/castilla-la-mancha/miguel-falcon-segundo-de-onesimo-nuevo-entrenador-del-cd-toledo/ |accessdate=17 November 2019 |publisher=En Castilla La Mancha |date=24 January 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref> In June, after being [[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|unable to prevent relegation]], he was given a job in the club's academy.<ref>{{cite news |title=El Toledo elige a Fran Cano para devolver al equipo a Segunda B |trans-title=Toledo choose Fran Cano as the man to return the team to Segunda B|url=https://www.abc.es/espana/castilla-la-mancha/toledo/deportes/abci-fran-cano-nuevo-entrenador-toledo-201806071147_noticia.html |accessdate=17 November 2019 |work=ABC |date=7 June 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|24 March 2018}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\t\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\t\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[CD Toledo|Toledo]]\n|{{Flagicon|Spain}}\t\n|align=left|24 January 2018\t\n|aligb=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|9|4|2|3|for=9|against=8|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l4629.html?temp=2017-18|title=Falc\u00f3n: Miguel Falc\u00f3n Garc\u00eda-Ramos|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref>\t\t\n|-\t\t\n| colspan=4 | '''Career Total'''\n{{WDLtot|9|4|2|3|for=9|against=8|diff=yes}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|4629|Miguel Falc\u00f3n}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|4629}}\n\n{{CD Toledo managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Falcon, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Toledo, Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Castilian-Manchegan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid C players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B players]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9rida UD footballers]]\n[[Category:CD Legan\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:Ciudad de Murcia footballers]]\n[[Category:Granada 74 CF footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Cartagena footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo players]]\n[[Category:CD Toledo players]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:CD Toledo managers]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor tidyups overall, nothing hurt whatsoever.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miguel_Falc%C3%B3n"}
{"title_page": "Ikastola", "text_new": "An '''{{lang|eu|Ikastola}}''' ({{IPA-eu|ikas\u033atola}}, plural {{lang|eu|ikastolak}}) is a type of primary and secondary school in the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Autonomous Community]], [[Navarre]] and (to a much lesser extent) the [[French Basque Country]] (see [[Basque Country (historical territory)|Basque Country]]) in which pupils are taught either entirely or predominantly in the [[Basque language]]. Ikastolak can be nowadays either private or public, divided into different networks.\n\nThe Basque language public network relies on state funding and management, allocated in Spain by the education institutions of the Basque Autonomous Community and Navarre in their corresponding territories, while in France the association Ikas-Bi in the public network advocates for bilingual education. Seaska is the private network of Basque language schools in the French Basque Country, closely linked to the similar network in the [[Southern Basque Country]]. The private networks base their activity on the fees paid by parents, popular subscription (either directly or by means of annual massive festivals, e.g. ''[[Herri Urrats]]'', ''[[Nafarroa Oinez]]'', ''[[Araba Euskaraz]]'', etc.) and the allowance provided by public educational institutions.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Sanpelaio4.jpg|200px|thumb|right|The Salbatore Mitxelena ikastola of [[Zarautz]]]]\nAlthough spoken more widely than in later times, there was very little schooling undertaken in Basque before the early 20th century revival in [[Basque nationalism]]. Spanish and French were mandatory in schooling at either side of the border. The first official ikastola was opened in 1914, and the movement to transfer the medium of education in the [[Southern Basque Country]] from [[Spanish language|Spanish]] to Basque became widespread in the late 20th century. \n\nDuring the early 1930s, the seeds of the \"Basque Schools\" (''Escuelas Vascas'') were sown  in [[Navarre]] by the Basque Nationalist Party, featuring an instruction where the teachings of the Christian doctrine were central. They were conceived as an attempt to counter increased laicization of state schools and the lack of focus (\"the neutrality\") on Basque matters in regular religious schooling. The first such educative institution was founded in November 1931 at Pamplona, followed by another one in [[Estella-Lizarra]] (1933) and Elizondo (1935).<ref>{{cite book |last=Dronda |first=Javier |date=2013 |title=Con Cristo o contra Cristo: Religi\u00f3n y movilizaci\u00f3n antirrepublicana en Navarra (1931-1936)|url= |location=Tafalla |publisher=Txalaparta |page=300 |isbn=978-84-15313-31-1 |accessdate= }}</ref>   \n\nFollowing the Republican defeat in the [[Spanish Civil War]], the public use of [[Basque language|Basque]] was [[Language politics in Spain under Franco|made illegal]], and all educational institutions were forced to teach entirely through the medium of [[Spanish language|Castilian]], to the complete neglect and persecution of Basque. There are, however, isolated examples of ikastolak which clandestinely continued to teach in Basque. \n\nSince thousands of children were studying out of the authorized schools and hence forbidden to progress to higher education, in 1969 the Roman Catholic Church arranged with the parent associations the lawful Diocesan Federation of Ikastolas, later becoming a secular federation. With the return of democracy following the death of [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] in 1975, large degrees of self-government were given to the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Autonomous Community]] and [[Navarre]], and ikastolak sprang up all over the [[Southern Basque Country|Basque region]] in northern [[Spain]].\n\nFor a time, the ikastolak operated along the public school system, the private schools publicly funded under a charter and the private schools. During his term as Basque minister for education, the [[Partido Socialista de Euskadi|Socialist]] [[Fernando Buesa]] proposed the 1993 Law of the Basque Public School, prompting ikastolak to choose between full integration in the public system or operating under the rules for chartered private schools.\n\nAt the present time, tens of thousands of schoolchildren in the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Autonomous Community]] and [[Navarre]] attend ikastolak, but the status of ikastolak differs greatly depending on their location. They are firmly entrenched in the traditionally Basque-speaking areas of the Basque Autonomous Community (BAC), but less so in non-Basque speaking areas (i.e. the southern fringes). Basque language schools in the north of Navarre do not enjoy the same support from the regional government as they do in the BAC, but they are officially recognised and enjoy widespread local support (traditionally Basque speaking), unlike central and southern areas of Navarre, where they lack public recognition and funding, remaining in a legal limbo until 2007.\n\nIn the French Basque Country, the ikastolak developed later, but grew steadily, so much so that a network, [[Seaska]], is now widespread throughout the whole territory covering education up to the A levels.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Basque education system]]\n* [[Breton language]] [[Diwan schools]]\n* [[Euskal Herriak Bere Eskola]]\n* [[Irish language]] [[Gaelscoil]]eana\n* [[Welsh language|Welsh]] [[Welsh medium education]]\n* [[Scottish Gaelic]] [[Gaelic medium education in Scotland|Gaelic medium education]]\n* [[Catalan language]] [[La Bressola]]\n* [[Occitan language]] [[Calandreta]]s\n* Illegal [[German language]] [[Katakombenschule]] in Italian Tyrol.\n* [[Greek language]] [[Krifo scholio]] during the Ottoman occupation\n* [[Galician language]] [[A gali\u00f1a azul]] in [[Galiza]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|Ikastolak|lcfirst=yes}}\nOfficial site of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070203130928/http://www.ikastola.net/web/default.php Federation of Ikastolak] (Basque)\n\n[[Category:Basque culture]]\n[[Category:Education in Spain]]\n[[Category:Education in France]]\n[[Category:Minority schools]]\n[[Category:Education in the Basque Country]]\n", "text_old": "An '''Ikastola''' ({{IPA-eu|ikas\u033atola}}, plural ''ikastolak'') is a type of primary and secondary school in the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Autonomous Community]], [[Navarre]] and (to a much lesser extent) the [[French Basque Country]] (see [[Basque Country (historical territory)|Basque Country]]) in which pupils are taught either entirely or predominantly in the [[Basque language]]. Ikastolak can be nowadays either private or public, divided into different networks.\n\nThe Basque language public network relies on state funding and management, allocated in Spain by the education institutions of the Basque Autonomous Community and Navarre in their corresponding territories, while in France the association Ikas-Bi in the public network advocates for bilingual education. Seaska is the private network of Basque language schools in the French Basque Country, closely linked to the similar network in the [[Southern Basque Country]]. The private networks base their activity on the fees paid by parents, popular subscription (either directly or by means of annual massive festivals, e.g. ''[[Herri Urrats]], [[Nafarroa Oinez]], [[Araba Euskaraz]]'', etc.) and the allowance provided by public educational institutions.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Sanpelaio4.jpg|200px|thumb|right|The Salbatore Mitxelena ikastola of [[Zarautz]]]]\nAlthough spoken more widely than in later times, there was very little schooling undertaken in Basque before the early 20th century revival in [[Basque nationalism]]. Spanish and French were mandatory in schooling at either side of the border. The first official ikastola was opened in 1914, and the movement to transfer the medium of education in the [[Southern Basque Country]] from [[Spanish language|Spanish]] to Basque became widespread in the late 20th century. \n\nDuring the early 1930s, the seeds of the \"Basque Schools\" (''Escuelas Vascas'') were sown  in [[Navarre]] by the Basque Nationalist Party, featuring an instruction where the teachings of the Christian doctrine were central. They were conceived as an attempt to counter increased laicization of state schools and the lack of focus (\"the neutrality\") on Basque matters in regular religious schooling. The first such educative institution was founded in November 1931 at Pamplona, followed by another one in [[Estella-Lizarra]] (1933) and Elizondo (1935).<ref>{{cite book |last=Dronda |first=Javier |date=2013 |title=Con Cristo o contra Cristo: Religi\u00f3n y movilizaci\u00f3n antirrepublicana en Navarra (1931-1936)|url= |location=Tafalla |publisher=Txalaparta |page=300 |isbn=978-84-15313-31-1 |accessdate= }}</ref>   \n\nFollowing the Republican defeat in the [[Spanish Civil War]], the public use of [[Basque language|Basque]] was [[Language politics in Spain under Franco|made illegal]], and all educational institutions were forced to teach entirely through the medium of [[Spanish language|Castilian]], to the complete neglect and persecution of Basque. There are, however, isolated examples of ikastolak which clandestinely continued to teach in Basque. \n\nSince thousands of children were studying out of the authorized schools and hence forbidden to progress to higher education, in 1969 the Roman Catholic Church arranged with the parent associations the lawful Diocesan Federation of Ikastolas, later becoming a secular federation. With the return of democracy following the death of [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] in 1975, large degrees of self-government were given to the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Autonomous Community]] and [[Navarre]], and ikastolak sprang up all over the [[Southern Basque Country|Basque region]] in northern [[Spain]].\n\nFor a time, the ikastolak operated along the public school system, the private schools publicly funded under a charter and the private schools. During his term as Basque minister for education, the [[Partido Socialista de Euskadi|Socialist]] [[Fernando Buesa]] proposed the 1993 Law of the Basque Public School, prompting ikastolak to choose between full integration in the public system or operating under the rules for chartered private schools.\n\nAt the present time, tens of thousands of schoolchildren in the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Autonomous Community]] and [[Navarre]] attend ikastolak, but the status of ikastolak differs greatly depending on their location. They are firmly entrenched in the traditionally Basque-speaking areas of the Basque Autonomous Community (BAC), but less so in non-Basque speaking areas (i.e. the southern fringes). Basque language schools in the north of Navarre do not enjoy the same support from the regional government as they do in the BAC, but they are officially recognised and enjoy widespread local support (traditionally Basque speaking), unlike central and southern areas of Navarre, where they lack public recognition and funding, remaining in a legal limbo until 2007.\n\nIn the French Basque Country, the ikastolak developed later, but grew steadily, so much so that a network, [[Seaska]], is now widespread throughout the whole territory covering education up to the A levels.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Basque education system]]\n* [[Breton language]] [[Diwan schools]]\n* [[Euskal Herriak Bere Eskola]]\n* [[Irish language]] [[Gaelscoil]]eana\n* [[Welsh language|Welsh]] [[Welsh medium education]]\n* [[Scottish Gaelic]] [[Gaelic medium education in Scotland|Gaelic medium education]]\n* [[Catalan language]] [[La Bressola]]\n* [[Occitan language]] [[Calandreta]]s\n* Illegal [[German language]] [[Katakombenschule]] in Italian Tyrol.\n* [[Greek language]] [[Krifo scholio]] during the Ottoman occupation\n* [[Galician language]] [[A gali\u00f1a azul]] in [[Galiza]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|Ikastolak|lcfirst=yes}}\nOfficial site of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070203130928/http://www.ikastola.net/web/default.php Federation of Ikastolak] (Basque)\n\n[[Category:Basque culture]]\n[[Category:Education in Spain]]\n[[Category:Education in France]]\n[[Category:Minority schools]]\n[[Category:Education in the Basque Country]]\n", "name_user": "OwenBlacker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Language tagging", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ikastola"}
{"title_page": "The Interview", "text_new": "{{short description|2014 film directed by Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg}}\n{{about|the 2014 film||Interview (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Interview\n| image          = The Interview 2014 poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster{{efn|The [[Korean language|Korean]] text translates as: \"The war will begin\" (on the missiles and tanks). The Korean text line right beneath the stars' names above the movie title translates to: \"Please do not believe these ignorant dishonorable Americans!\" while the small text to the left and right of the title, meanwhile, translates to the film's title. The fine print at the bottom of the poster reiterates the opening tagline from the top of the poster, translating to: \"Awful work by the 'pigs' that created ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'' and ''[[This Is the End]]''{{-\"}}.<ref>Vary, Adam B. (June 11, 2014). [https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill#.nq6r90dzZ3 \"The Poster For Seth Rogen and James Franco's New Comedy Is Filled with Anti-American Propaganda\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328132022/http://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill |date=March 28, 2016 }}. [[BuzzFeed]]. Retrieved December 21, 2014.</ref>}}\n| director       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Evan Goldberg]]\n}}\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* James Weaver\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Dan Sterling]]\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* Dan Sterling\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Franco]]\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Randall Park]]\n<!--per billing block-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Henry Jackman]]\n| cinematography = [[Brandon Trost]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Zene Baker]]\n* Evan Henke\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Point Grey Pictures]]\n* [[LStar Capital]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]{{efn|All references to [[Sony Pictures]] were removed from the final film and marketing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |title=Hack Attack: Sony Orders Its Name Removed from \u2018Interview\u2019 Marketing Materials |url=https://www.thewrap.com/hack-attack-sony-orders-its-name-removed-from-interview-marketing-materials/ |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=December 12, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|12|11|Los Angeles|2014|12|24|United States<!--- This is for the on demand date, and the film was only released on December 24. Please go to the talk page before changing this --->}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 111:49 --><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | title=''The Interview'' (15) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 17, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129045957/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | archivedate=November 29, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Korean\n}}\n| budget         = $44 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|title=Sony Weighing Premium VOD Release for 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 17, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=January 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116144807/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|title=Sony Could Lose $75 Million on 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 18, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220194759/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = $12.3 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | title = The Interview (2014) \u2013 Financial Information | work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = May 1, 2019  | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180422062312/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | archivedate = April 22, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Interview''''' is a 2014 American [[action comedy film]] co-produced and directed by [[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] in their second directorial work, following ''[[This Is the End]]'' (2013). The screenplay was written by [[Dan Sterling]], based on a story he co-wrote with Rogen and Goldberg. The film stars Rogen and [[James Franco]] as journalists who set up an interview with [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ([[Randall Park]]), and are then recruited by the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] to assassinate him. The film is heavily inspired by a 2012 ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' documentary.\n\nRogen and Goldberg developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, with [[Kim Jong-il]] as the original assassination target. In 2011, after [[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|Jong-il's death]] and Jong-un's succession as the [[List of heads of state of North Korea|North Korean leader]], Rogen and Goldberg redeveloped the script with the focus on Jong-un's character. ''The Interview'' was first announced in March 2013, at the beginning of pre-production. [[Principal photography]] was in [[Vancouver]] from October to December 2013. The film was produced by [[Columbia Pictures]], [[LStar Capital]] and Rogen and Goldberg's [[Point Grey Pictures]], and distributed by [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]].\n\nIn June 2014, the North Korean government threatened action against the United States if Sony released the film. As a result, Sony delayed the release from October to December and reportedly re-edited the film to make it more acceptable to North Korea. In November, the computer systems of Sony were [[Sony Pictures hack|hacked]] by the \"Guardians of Peace\", a group the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] claimed has ties to North Korea.<ref>[[Gabi Siboni]] and David Siman-Tov, [http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf Cyberspace Extortion: North Korea versus the United States] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820031432/http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf |date=August 20, 2016 }}, [[Institute for National Security Studies (Israel)|INSS]] Insight No. 646, December 23, 2014.</ref> The group also threatened terrorist attacks against theaters showing the film. As a result, major theater chains opted not to release the film, and Sony instead released it for online digital rental and purchase on December 24, 2014, followed by a [[limited release]] at selected theaters the next day.\n\nIn December 2014, [[South Korea|South Korean]] singer [[Yoon Mi-rae]] revealed that the film used her song \"Pay Day\" without permission, and that she was taking legal action.<ref name=\"newsmp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.soompi.com/2014/12/26/yoon-mi-rae-to-take-legal-action-against-sony-pictures-for-using-her-song-in-the-interview-without-permission/|title=Yoon Mi Rae to Take Legal Action against Sony Pictures for Using Her Song in \"The Interview\" without Permission|date=27 December 2014|work=Soompi|author=|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> Yoon Mi-rae and her label [[Feel Ghood Music]] reached a settlement with Sony Pictures Entertainment on the 13th of May 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/201343/20150517/sony-the-interview-yoon-mi-rae-payday.htm|title=Sony And Yoon Mi Rae Reach Settlement Over Unlicensed Song Usage In 'The Interview'|website=KpopStarz|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> \n\n''The Interview'' grossed $40 million in digital rentals, making it Sony's most successful digital release and earned an additional $12.3 million worldwide in box office ticket sales on a $44 million budget. It received mixed reviews for its humor and subject matter, although a few critics praised the performances of Rogen, Franco, Park and [[Diana Bang]].\n\n==Plot==\nDave Skylark is the host of the [[talk show]] ''Skylark Tonight'', where he interviews various celebrities about personal topics and gossip. After Skylark and his crew celebrate their producer Aaron Rapaport's 1,000th episode, Rapaport is upset by a producer peer who criticized the show as not being a real news program. Rapaport reveals his concern and urge for change, to which Skylark agrees. Later, Skylark discovers that [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] is a fan of ''Skylark Tonight'', prompting Rapaport to arrange an interview for him. Rapaport travels to a place outside [[Dandong]], [[China]] to receive instructions from Sook-yin Park, the [[Propaganda in North Korea|North Korean chief propagandist]], and Rapaport accepts the task of interviewing Kim on behalf of Skylark.\n\nThe next day, [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent Lacey shows up at Skylark and Rapaport's place, proposing that the duo assassinate Kim using a [[Transdermal patch|transdermal strip]] that will expose Kim to [[ricin]] via handshake; they reluctantly agree. Skylark carries the ricin strip hidden inside a pack of gum. Upon their arrival in the [[Residences of North Korean leaders|presidential palace]] in [[Pyongyang]], they are introduced to security officers Koh and Yu; Koh discovers the strip and chews it, believing it to be gum. That night, Lacey airdrops them two more strips from a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]], but in order to smuggle it back to their room, Rapaport has to evade a [[Siberian tiger]] and then hide the container in his rectum. Later, Kim shows up and introduces himself to Skylark.\n\nSkylark spends the day with Kim by playing [[basketball]], hanging out and partying together. Kim persuades Skylark that he is misunderstood as both a cruel dictator and a failed administrator, and they become friends. At dinner, Koh has a [[Epileptic seizure|seizure]] due to the ricin poisoning and accidentally shoots Yu before dying. The next morning, Skylark feels guilty and discards one of the ricin strips, then thwarts Rapaport's attempt to poison Kim with the second strip. After another dinner mourning the death of Kim's bodyguards, Skylark witnesses Kim's malicious side as he [[Korean conflict|threatens war]] against [[South Korea]] and \"every single enemy of his country\". Skylark leaves and after taking a walk, he discovers that a nearby grocery store is merely [[Potemkin village|fake]] and realizes that Kim has been lying to him. At the same time, during an attempted sex with Rapaport (who still has the ricin strip in his hand), Sook-yin reveals that she despises Kim and apologizes for defending the regime. Skylark, Rapaport and Sook-yin plan to ruin [[Kim Jong-un's cult of personality|Kim's cult of personality]] by causing him to cry on air. Before the broadcast starts, Kim gives Skylark a puppy as a gift to keep.\n\nDuring the internationally televised interview with Kim, Skylark addresses increasingly sensitive topics (including the country's [[North Korean famine|food shortage]] issues and [[Sanctions against North Korea|economic sanctions]] imposed by the US) and challenges Kim's need for [[Kim Jong-il|his father]]'s approval. Meanwhile, Sook-yin and Rapaport seize control of the broadcasting center and attack guards trying to cut off the broadcast. Despite his initial resistance, Kim eventually cries uncontrollably and soils himself after Skylark sings [[Firework (song)|\"Firework\"]] by [[Katy Perry]] (having learned of Kim's fondness of Perry earlier), ruining his reputation. Feeling betrayed and labeling Skylark as a \"fake friend\", Kim shoots him and leaves, but Skylark survives due to a [[bulletproof vest]]. Skylark, Rapaport and Sook-yin regroup (with the puppy in tow) and escape the presidential palace with the unexpected help of a panel-control guard. The trio hijack Kim's [[T-54/T-55|personal tank]], originally given to [[Kim Il-sung]] by [[Joseph Stalin]], to get to their pickup point. Kim boards a helicopter while his own army attacks the group. He prepares a nuclear missile launch, but before he can issue the command to launch, Skylark shoots down Kim's helicopter, killing him. \n\nWith the immediate threat over, Sook guides Skylark and Rapaport to an escape route where they are rescued and loaded onto a rescue craft by three [[SEAL Team Six]] members disguised as [[Korean People's Army]] troops, while Sook goes to [[Pyongyang]] to ensure political stability. Back in the United States, Skylark writes a book about his experience while North Korea become [[denuclearization|denuclearized]] and [[democratization|democratized]] under Sook-yin, who steps in as an [[Transitional government|interim]] leader.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Franco]] as Dave Skylark\n* [[Seth Rogen]] as Aaron Rapaport\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as Agent Lacey\n* [[Randall Park]] as [[Kim Jong-un]]\n* [[Diana Bang]] as Sook-yin Park\n* [[Timothy Simons]] as Malcolm\n<!-- these are listed after the main six in the longer closing credits -->\n* Reese Alexander as Agent Botwin\n* [[Anders Holm]] as Jake\n* [[Charles Chun|Charles Rahi Chun]] as General Jong\n* [[Ben Schwartz]] as Daryl\n<!-- ones listed after here were minor characters such as Two-Fingered Man, Train Passengers, Korean Girl, Hot Korean Girls, Drone Pilot, etc. -->\n\nThe film also features [[cameo appearance]]s from [[Eminem]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Bill Maher]], [[Seth Meyers]], [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]], [[Brian Williams]] and [[Scott Pelley]]. [[Iggy Azalea]], [[Nicki Minaj]], [[Emma Stone]], [[Zac Efron]] and [[Guy Fieri]] appear in the title graphic card for ''Skylark Tonight''.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, joking about what would happen if a journalist was required to assassinate a world leader.<ref name=\"December2014RS\">{{cite journal| first =Josh| last =Eells| date =December 17, 2014| title =Seth Rogen at the Crossroads| journal =[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]| issue =1224/1225| pages =52\u201357; 86| location =[[New York City]]| issn =0035-791X| url =https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| accessdate =December 17, 2014| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141225013015/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| archivedate =December 25, 2014| df =mdy-all}}</ref>\nInitially, screenwriter [[Dan Sterling]] wrote his script involving a fictional dictator from a fictional country, but Rogen, Goldberg and Sony executives asked him to rewrite the script focusing on Kim.<ref name=\"Maroff\">{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|title=The Interview: an \"Act of War\"|last=Maroff|first=Melissa|date=December 18, 2014|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|accessdate=July 21, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150721111520/http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|archivedate=July 21, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The screenplay was then titled ''Kill Kim Jong Un''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weinstein|first1=Shelli|title=Seth Rogen: Censoring North Korea in 'The Interview' 'Seemed Wrong'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|accessdate=February 6, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 4, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205115351/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|archivedate=February 5, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Previous iterations of the story revolved around [[Kim Jong-il]], but put the project on hold until Jong-il died and his son [[Kim Jong-un]] assumed power in 2011. Development resumed when Rogen and Goldberg realized that Jong-un is closer to their own age, which they felt would be more humorous. To write the story, co-written with ''[[Daily Show]]'' writer [[Dan Sterling]], they researched meticulously by reading non-fiction books and watching video footage about North Korea. The script was later reviewed by an employee in the [[United States Department of State|State Department]].<ref name=Jan2015NewYorker>{{cite news|last1=Demick|first1=Barbara|title=A North Korea Watcher Watches \"The Interview\"|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|accessdate=July 7, 2015|work=newyorker.com|date=January 2, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714153529/http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|archivedate=July 14, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg aimed to make the project more relevant and satirical than their previous films while retaining [[toilet humor]].<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> They were pleased when former [[NBA]] star [[Dennis Rodman]] visited North Korea, as it reinforced their belief that the premise of the film was realistic.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-production===\nIn March 2013, it was announced that Rogen and Goldberg would direct a comedy film for [[Columbia Pictures]] in which Rogen would star alongside [[James Franco]], with Franco playing a talk-show host and Rogen playing his producer.<ref name=March2013THR>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Seth Rogen to Direct, Star in 'The Interview' for Columbia Pictures (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=March 21, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613020954/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|archivedate=June 13, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg were on board to produce along with James Weaver through [[Point Grey Pictures]], while Columbia was said to finance the $30 million budgeted film.<ref name=\"March2013THR\" /> [[Lizzy Caplan]] joined the film's cast in October 2013. Caplan signed on to play Agent Lacey, a CIA agent who tries to get Franco's character to assassinate the Korean prime minister.<ref name=October2013THR>{{cite news|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Lizzy Caplan Joins Seth Rogen and James Franco in 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232251/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Randall Park]] and [[Timothy Simons]] signed on to co-star later that month. Park plays the North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-Un]] and Simons the director of the talk show.<ref name=October2013THR1>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Randall Park and 'Veep's' Timothy Simons to Co-Star in Seth Rogen's 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=October 8, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420010237/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|archivedate=April 20, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | title=North Korea Calls Seth Rogen-James Franco Film An 'Act Of War' | work=The Huffington Post | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | author=Mazza, Ed | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627132111/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | archivedate=June 27, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Park was the first to audition for the role of Kim and got the part immediately.  Before filming began, Park gained 15 pounds and shaved his head to resemble Jong-un's [[crew cut]].  His role was praised by critics.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /><ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /> Although Rogen and Goldberg wrote the character of Kim as \"robotic and strict\", Park instead played it \"sheepish and shy\", which they found more humorous.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> [[Diana Bang]] was cast as Sook-yin Park, for which she was well received by critics.<ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |title=''The Interview'' Actress Diana Bang Is Ready for Anything |author=Smith, Krista |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 20, 2014 |accessdate=December 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217174628/http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |archivedate=December 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], on October 10, 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last=Schaefer|first=Glen|title=Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg come home to shoot B.C. for Korea in The Interview|url=http://blogs.theprovince.com/2013/10/12/seth-rogen-and-evan-goldberg-come-home-to-shoot-b-c-for-korea-in-the-interview/|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Province|date=October 12, 2013}}</ref> and concluded on December 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Seth Rogen, Evan Goldberg to Direct 'The Interview' in Vancouver|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 30, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232252/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> There are hundreds of visual effects in the film;  a crowd scene at the Pyongyang airport, for example, was digitally manipulated with a shot from ''[[22 Jump Street]]''.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-release reaction===\nIn June 2014, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that the film had \"touched a nerve\" within the North Korean government, as they are \"notoriously paranoid about perceived threats to their safety.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title=North Korea threatens 'merciless' response over Seth Rogen film|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|work=The Guardian|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418173750/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|archivedate=April 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianBranigan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|title=Sony's cancellation of ''The Interview'' surprises North Korea-watchers|last=Branigan|first=Tanya|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220190356/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Korean Central News Agency]] (KCNA), the state news agency of North Korea, reported that their government  promised \"stern\" and \"merciless\" retaliation if the film was released. KCNA said that the release of a film portraying the assassination of the North Korean leader would not be allowed and it would be considered the \"most blatant act of terrorism and war.\"<ref name=\"North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war'\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | title=North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war' | publisher=CBC News | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626045743/http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | archivedate=June 26, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea threatens war on US over Kim Jong-un movie|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=BBC|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625140625/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|archivedate=June 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The next month, North Korea's [[Permanent Representative to the United Nations|United Nations ambassador]] Ja Song-nam condemned the film, describing its production and distribution as \"an act of war\" and because of Kim's assassination in the film, \"the most undisguised sponsoring of terrorism.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\">{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |title=North Korea complains to UN about Seth Rogen comedy The Interview |work=The Guardian |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 30, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730031714/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |archivedate=July 30, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''The Guardian''  described Song-nam's comments as \"perfect publicity for the movie.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\" /> Later in July, KCNA wrote to U.S. President [[Barack Obama]], asking to have the film pulled.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Julian|title=North Korea appeals to White House to halt release of US comedy film|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=July 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812122012/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|archivedate=August 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Shortly before the planned release of the film on December 25, 2014, screenwriter Dan Sterling told ''Creative Screenwriting:'' \"I couldn't believe that the most infamous man in the world knew about my script \u2013 but most importantly, I would never want something I wrote to lead to some kind of humanitarian disaster. I would be horrified if anyone got hurt over this.\"<ref name=\"Maroff\"/>\n\n==Release==\n===Delay and changes===\nIn August 2014, Sony delayed the film's release from October 10 to December 25, 2014.<ref name=\"release\">{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' with Seth Rogen, James Franco Pushed Back to Christmas|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|accessdate=August 7, 2014|work=Variety|date=August 7, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810035632/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|archivedate=August 10, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Sony made post-production alterations to the film to modify its portrayal of North Korea, including modifying the designs of buttons worn by characters, originally modeled after real North Korean military buttons praising the country's leaders, and cutting a portion of Kim Jong-un's death scene.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Sony Altering Kim Jong Un Assassination Film 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 13, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815064109/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|archivedate=August 15, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sony Pictures Entertainment hack and threats===\n{{main|Sony Pictures hack}}\n[[File:Sony Pictures Entertainment entrance 1.jpg|right|thumb|A hacker group compromised much of Sony Pictures Entertainment's computer system in late 2014 in retaliation for the film's content.]]\nOn November 24, 2014, an anonymous group identifying themselves as the \"Guardians of Peace\" hacked the computer networks of Columbia Pictures's parent company Sony Pictures Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sanger|first1=David E.|last2=Perlroth|first2=Nicole|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|title=U.S. Said to Find North Korea Ordered Cyberattack on Sony|work=The New York Times|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218130909/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The hackers [[Internet leak|leaked]] internal emails, employee records and several recent and unreleased Sony Pictures films, including ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'', ''[[Mr. Turner (film)|Mr. Turner]]'', ''[[Still Alice]]'', and ''[[To Write Love on Her Arms (film)|To Write Love on Her Arms]]''. The North Korean government denied involvement in the hack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|title=North Korea denies hacking Sony Pictures|first=Justin|last=McCurry|work=The Guardian|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218083138/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\">{{cite news|title=Hackers who targeted Sony invoke 9/11 attacks in warning to moviegoers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|accessdate=December 17, 2014|work=The Guardian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217042527/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sony's New Movies Leak Online Following Hack Attack|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|website=NBC News|accessdate=December 1, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202203232/http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|archivedate=December 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 8, the hackers leaked further materials, including a demand that Sony pull \"the movie of terrorism\", widely interpreted as referring to ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hackers told Sony to pull 'The Interview'|first=Elizabeth|last=Weise|work=USA Today|date=December 9, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130004703/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|archivedate=November 30, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korean Government Thought To Be Behind Sony Pictures Hack|date=December 1, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424234518/http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|archivedate=April 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea's Cyber Skills Get Attention Amid Sony Hacking Mystery|date=December 4, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407195600/http://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|archivedate=April 7, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2014, the hackers threatened to attack the [[New York City|New York]] premiere of ''The Interview'' and any cinema showing the film.<ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\" /> Two further messages were released on December 1; one, sent in a private message to Sony executives, said that the hackers would not release further information if Sony never released the film and removed it from the internet. The other, posted to [[Pastebin]], a web application used for text storage which the Guardians of Peace had used for previous messages, stated that Sony had \"suffered enough\" and could release ''The Interview'', but only if Kim Jong-un's death scene was not \"too happy\". The message also threatened that if Sony made another film antagonizing North Korea, the hackers \"will be here ready to fight\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weise |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Johnson |first2=Kevin |title=Obama: Sony \"did the wrong thing\" when it pulled movie |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=December 19, 2014 |accessdate=December 19, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219204906/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |archivedate=December 19, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Distribution===\n''The Interview'' was not released in Japan, as live-action comedy films do not often perform well in the market. In the Asia-Pacific region, it was released only in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|title='The Interview' to Have Only Limited Release in Asia|date=December 10, 2014|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last1=Schilling|first1=Mark|accessdate=December 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213194607/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|archivedate=December 13, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nRogen predicted that the film would make its way to North Korea, stating that \"we were told one of the reasons they're so against the movie is that they're afraid it'll actually get into North Korea. They do have [[Bootleg recording|bootlegs]] and stuff. Maybe the tapes will make their way to North Korea and cause a revolution.\"<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> ''[[Business Insider]]'' reported via [[Free North Korea Radio]] that there was high demand for bootleg copies of the film in North Korea.<ref name=\"BI\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Eugene|title=Demand For 'The Interview' Is Shooting Up In North Korea And Its Government Is Freaking Out|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|website=Business Insider|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229032411/http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The South Korean [[human rights organization]]s [[Fighters for a Free North Korea]] and [[Human Rights Foundation]], largely made up of North Korean defectors, planned to distribute DVD copies of ''The Interview'' [[Balloon campaigns in Korea|via balloon drops]].<ref name=\"hr20141216\">{{cite news|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2014|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|title=Sony Hack: Activists to Drop 'Interview' DVDs Over North Korea Via Balloon|first=Paul|last=Bond|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217073943/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|title=Launching Balloons into North Korea: Propaganda Over Pyongyang|date=18 March 2015|work=VICE news|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402162347/https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The groups had previously air-dropped offline copies of the [[Korean Wikipedia]] into North Korea on a [[bootable USB]] memory device.<ref name=\"cnn20141218\">{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|title=Activists plan to drop 'Interview' DVDs in North Korea|last=Segall|first=Laurie|publisher=CNN|authorlink=Laurie Segall|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220202241/http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The balloon drop was scrapped after the North Korean government referred to the plan as a [[de facto]] \"declaration of war.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|title=South Korean activists postpone sending of copies of The Interview to North Korea by balloon|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=24 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323214646/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|archivedate=March 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|title=North Korea Calls Planned Balloon Drop of 'The Interview' DVDs a 'De Facto Declaration of War'|first=Gillian|last=Mohney|date=23 March 2015|work=VICE News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094846/https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation of wide theatrical release===\nThe [[Film premiere|premiere]] was held in [[Los Angeles]] on December 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|title='The Interview' Premiere: Seth Rogen Thanks Amy Pascal \"For Having The Balls to Make This Movie\"|first=Tim|last=Appelo|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217202418/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film scheduled a [[wide release]] in the UK and Ireland on February 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | title = 'The Interview' To Get Wide Release In The UK | first = Ali | last = Jaafar | publisher = Deadline.com | date = January 7, 2015 | accessdate = January 12, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150110034332/http://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | archivedate = January 10, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Following the hackers' threats on December 16, Rogen and Franco canceled scheduled publicity appearances and Sony pulled all television advertising.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|title=Seth Rogen and James Franco Cancel All Media Appearances for 'The Interview'|work=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216230918/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|archivedate=December 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] said that they would not object to cinema owners delaying the film to ensure the safety of filmgoers. Shortly afterwards, the [[ArcLight Hollywood|ArcLight]] and [[Carmike Cinemas|Carmike]] cinema chains announced that they would not screen the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|title=First Theaters Cancel 'The Interview' After Hacker Threats|first1=Jen|last1=Yamato|first2=Dominic|last2=Patten|work=Deadline|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217055402/http://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, Sony canceled the New York City premiere. Later that day, other major theater chains including [[AMC Theatres|AMC]], [[Cinemark Theatres|Cinemark]], [[Cineplex Entertainment|Cineplex]], [[Regal Entertainment Group|Regal]] and [[Southern Theatres]] either delayed or canceled screenings of the film.<ref name=\"variety-interviewdropped\">{{cite web|title=Major U.S. Theaters Drop 'The Interview' After Sony Hacker Threats|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141217061335/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The chains reportedly came under pressure from [[shopping mall]]s where many theaters are located, which feared that the terror threat would ruin their holiday sales. They also feared expensive lawsuits in the event of an attack; Cinemark, for instance, contended that it could not have foreseen the [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting]], which took place at one of its multiplexes, a defense that would not hold in the event of an attack at a screening of ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|title=Sony Drops 'The Interview' Following Terrorist Threats|first1=Brooks|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael|last2=Cieply|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129055352/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|archivedate=January 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe cancellation also affected other films in which each films' subject matter is North Korea. An [[Alamo Drafthouse Cinema]] location in [[Dallas]] planned to hold a free screening of ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', which satirizes Kim Jong-un's father [[Kim Jong-il]], in place of its previously scheduled screening of ''The Interview'';<ref name=\"thr-tawp\">{{cite web|title=Texas Theater to Show 'Team America' In Place of 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218054150/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"variety-tawpdallas\">{{cite web|title='Team America: World Police' Replaces 'The Interview' at Dallas Theater|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218051139/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Paramount Pictures]] refused to permit the screening.<ref name=\"deadline-tawpcancelled\">{{cite web|title=Paramount Cancels 'Team America' Showings, Theaters Say|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218215711/https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[New Regency]] pulled out of a planned film adaptation of the graphic novel ''[[Pyongyang: A Journey in North Korea|Pyongyang]]'' starring [[Steve Carell]]; Carell declared it a \"sad day for creative expression\".<ref name=\"cbc-carellcancelled\">{{cite news|title=Steve Carell's North Korea movie from Guy Delisle novel scrapped after Sony hack|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|website=CBC News|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219202505/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|archivedate=December 19, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony received criticism for canceling the wide release.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last1=Sinha-Roy|first1=Piya|title=Hollywood slams Sony, movie theaters for canceling 'The Interview'|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|agency=Reuters|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211630/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcus|first1=Stephanie|title=Celebrities React To Sony Canceling 'The Interview' Release|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218111029/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|title=Hollywood Hits Twitter To Vent Anger About 'The Interview' Being Pulled|work=Deadline|date=December 17, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218045202/http://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Guardian'' film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]] wrote that it was an \"unprecedented defeat on American turf\", but that \"North Korea will find that their bullying edict will haunt them.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Peter|title=The Interview: Sony's retreat signals an unprecedented defeat on American turf|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219171059/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|archivedate=December 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''In the Capital'' and [[Gizmodo]] suggested the cancellation caused a [[Streisand effect]], whereby the attempt to remove or censor a work has the unintended consequence of publicizing it more widely.<ref name=\"itc20141215\">{{cite news |last1=Schwartz |first1=Eric Hal |title=Sony Pictures Is in for a Lesson on the Streisand Effect |url=http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |accessdate=December 20, 2014 |work=In The Capital |date=December 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218174836/http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |archivedate=December 18, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |title=The Streisand Effect and Why We All Now Want to See 'The Interview' |publisher=Gizmodo.co.uk |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227120034/http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |archivedate=December 27, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a press conference, U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] said that though he was sympathetic to Sony's need to protect employees, he thought Sony had \"made a mistake. We cannot have a society in which some dictator in some place can start imposing censorship in the United States. I wish they'd spoken to me first. I would have told them: do not get into the pattern in which you are intimidated.\"<ref name=\"obama\">{{cite news|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/obama-sony-made-mistake-canceling-film-release/story?id=27720800|title=Sony Hacking: President Obama Says Company Made 'Mistake' in Canceling 'The Interview'|first1=Devin|last1=Dwyer |first2=Mary|last2=Bruce|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO [[Michael Lynton]], the cancellation of the wide release was a response to the refusal of cinema chains to screen the film, not the hackers' threats, and that Sony would seek other ways to distribute the film. Sony released a statement saying that the company \"is and always has been strongly committed to the First Amendment ... Free expression should never be suppressed by threats and extortion.\"<ref name=\"hrdec19\" />\n\nThe movie was not released in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbth.com/arts/327422-banned-movies-russia|title=Final cut: Movies that have been banned in Russia|last=Tokmasheva|first=Maria|date=2018-01-30|website=www.rbth.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n===Revised release===\nAfter the wide release cancellation, Sony considered other ways to release the film, citing pressure from the film industry, theater owners, and the White House.<ref name=\"hrdec19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|title=Sony Fires Back at Obama: \"We Had No Choice\" But to Cancel 'The Interview' Release|first1=Tatiana|last1=Siegel|first2=Erik|last2=Hayden|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224170752/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|archivedate=December 24, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"whitehouseofficialinterviewresponsenbc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|title=Obama: Sony 'Made a Mistake' By Pulling 'The Interview' Movie|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=April 3, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403013318/http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|archivedate=April 3, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DecPressure\">{{cite news|last1=Atkinson|first1=Claire|title=Sony faces pressure to release 'The Interview'|url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=New York Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223122056/http://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[NBC News|NBC]]'s ''[[Meet the Press]]'' on December 21, Sony's legal counsel [[David Boies]] noted that the company was still committed to releasing the film.<ref name=\"DecPressure\" /> Sony planned a  [[limited release]] for December 25, 2014, at more than three hundred American independent and [[arthouse cinema]]s.<ref>Shaw, Lucas (December 23, 2014). [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html \"Sony to Release ''The Interview'' in More Than 300 Theaters on Christmas Day\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225220539/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}. ''[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]''. Retrieved December 26, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\" /><ref name=\"dp20141223\" /><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ 'Hobbit' rules box office, 'Interview' succeeds online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916012041/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ |date=September 16, 2017 }}. ''USA Today''. Retrieved December 29, 2014.</ref> Lynton stated that Sony was trying to show the film to the largest audience by securing as many theaters as they could.<ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\">{{cite web|title='The Interview' Release Back On For Christmas Day \u2013 Update|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223224802/https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"dp20141223\">{{cite web|last=Pankratz|first=Howard|title=Alamo Drafthouse in Littleton will screen 'The Interview' starting Christmas|url=http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=The Denver Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223221307/http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony released ''The Interview'' for rental or purchase in the United States through the [[Streaming media|streaming]] services [[Google Play]], [[Xbox Video]], and [[YouTube]] on December 24, 2014. It was also available for a limited time on SeeTheInterview.com, a website operated by the [[stealth startup]] Kernel.com, which Sony previously worked with to market ''[[The Fifth Wave (film)|The Fifth Wave]]''.<ref name=\"variety-kernel\">{{cite web|title=What is Kernel? The Stealth Startup Sony Tapped to Stream 'The Interview' (Exclusive)|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 30, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230054245/http://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|archivedate=December 30, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Within hours, ''The Interview'' spread to [[file sharing]] websites after a security hole allowed people to download rather than stream the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|title=Oops: people are downloading and keeping Sony's rental for The Interview|work=The Verge|accessdate=December 26, 2014|date=December 24, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226080153/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|archivedate=December 26, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[TorrentFreak]] estimated that ''The Interview'' had been downloaded illegally via [[BitTorrent|torrents]] at least 1.5 million times in just two days.<ref name=\"tf-theinterview\">{{cite web|title=The Interview Is A Pirate Hit With 200k Downloads (Updated)|url=http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225|website=[[TorrentFreak]]|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228135544/http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225/|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 27, the North Korean [[National Defence Commission]] released a statement accusing President Obama of forcing Sony to distribute the film.<ref name=\"bbc27/12/2014\">{{cite web|title=North Korea berates Obama over The Interview release|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|publisher=BBC News|date=December 27, 2014|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228161521/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on [[iTunes]] on December 28.<ref name=\"verge-15mill\">{{cite web|title=The Interview makes over $15 million online, beating movie theaters|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|website=The Verge|accessdate=December 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229020127/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the first week of January 2015, Sony announced ''The Interview'' would receive a wide theatrical release in the United Kingdom and Ireland on February 6, but it would not be distributed digitally in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |title=The Interview to receive UK release, Sony confirms |publisher=BBC News |date=January 7, 2015 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110053317/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |archivedate=January 10, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film became available for [[Streaming media|streaming]] on [[Netflix]] on January 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|title='The Interview' is on Netflix streaming|website=engadget.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601025257/http://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|archivedate=June 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nSony released the film on [[Blu-ray Disc]] and [[DVD]] on February 17, 2015. The home release was packaged as the \"Freedom Edition\", and included 90 minutes of [[deleted scene]]s, behind-the-scenes featurettes, a [[blooper]] reel, [[Audio commentary|feature commentary]] with directors Rogen and Goldberg, and a special episode of ''[[Naked and Afraid]]'' featuring Rogen and Franco.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Chris|title=The Interview is coming to Blu-ray and DVD on February 17th|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|accessdate=January 16, 2015|work=[[The Verge]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116121756/http://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> {{as of|df=US|2015|07|21|}}, the film had earned over $6.7 million in sales in the U.S.<ref name=\"TheNumbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | title = The Interview (2014) | publisher = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = July 21, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150703215408/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | archivedate = July 3, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office and online rentals===\n''The Interview'' opened to a limited release in the United States on December 25, 2014, across 331 theaters<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | title = 'The Interview' Release: 331= Nellie | last2 = Andreeva | publisher = Deadline.com | date = December 24, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226225615/http://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | archivedate = December 26, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and earned over $1 million on its opening day. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the opening gross \"an impressive launch for a title playing in only about 300 independent theaters in the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | title = Box Office: 'The Interview' Earns $1 Million on Christmas; 'Unbroken,' 'Into the Woods' Surging to $40M | first = Dave | last = McNarry | work = Variety | date = December 26, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141227125400/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | archivedate = December 27, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It went on to earn over $1.8 million in its opening weekend, and by the end of its run on January 25, 2015, had grossed $6.1 million at the box office.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3987&p=.htm | title = Weekend Report (cont.): Huge Limited Debuts for 'American Sniper,' 'Selma' | first = Ray | last = Subers | publisher = Box Office Mojo | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-statusBachelorette]]'' ($8.2 million), and ''[[Snowpiercer]]'' ($7 million).<ref name=\"VOD\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | title = Sony: 'The Interview' Has Made Over $15 Million Online | first = Brent | last = Lang | work = Variety | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141229012755/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | archivedate = December 29, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It is the top-selling [[Google Play]] and [[YouTube]] film of 2014.<ref>[http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ The Year's top-selling movie on YouTube, Google Play] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231195212/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ |date=December 31, 2014 }}. ''Entertainment Weekly''. Retrieved December 31, 2014.</ref> By January 20, 2015, the film had earned more than $40 million from online sales and rentals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' Makes $40 Million Online and On-Demand|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|accessdate=January 20, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20180116143833/https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|archivedate=January 16, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony expected ''The Interview'' to break even through video-on-demand sales and saving millions of dollars on marketing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Faughdner|first1=Ryan|title=Sony's 'The Interview' to get 'freedom edition' home video release|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|accessdate=January 17, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117094529/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|archivedate=January 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] contended that Sony would lose at least $30 million due to poor box office performance.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | title = 'The Interview' Lost Sony $30 Million, Says Theater Group | first = Pamela | last = McClintock | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date = January 16, 2015 | accessdate = January 17, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150120044501/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | archivedate = January 20, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 51% approval rating, based on 141 reviews, with an average rating of 5.6/10. The site's consensus reads: \"Unfortunately overshadowed by controversy (and under-screened as a result), ''The Interview''{{'}}s screenplay offers middling laughs bolstered by its two likable leads.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|title=The Interview (2014)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141222025822/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|archivedate=December 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 52 out of 100, based on 33 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|title=The Interview|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 18, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209073010/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|archivedate=February 9, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[IGN]]'s Roth Cornet wrote that \"though it's unlikely to stand out as one of the shrewdest political satires of its time, [it] is a clever, unrestrained and\u2014most importantly\u2014sidesplitting parody that pokes fun at both a vapid media and one of the world's most dangerous dictators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/12/the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=IGN.com}}</ref> Edward Douglas of [[CraveOnline|ComingSoon.net]] said the film was \"hilarious, but it will probably get us nuked.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=ComingSoon.net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229175043/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jordan Hoffman of ''The Guardian'' gave the film three out of five stars and wrote that \"if this unessential but agreeable movie really triggered an international response, this is life reflecting art in a major way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|title = The Interview review: stoned, anally fixated \u2013 and funny|date = December 12, 2014|accessdate = December 28, 2014|work = The Guardian|last = Hoffman|first = Jordan|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226005452/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|archivedate = December 26, 2014|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nScott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' panned the film as \"cinematic [[waterboarding]]\" and \"about as funny as a communist food shortage, and just as protracted\", but praised the performances of Randall Park and Diana Bang.<ref name=ScottFoundasVariety>{{cite web|last=Foundas|first=Scott|title=Film Review: 'The Interview'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225093148/http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293/|archivedate=December 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' also praised Park and Bang, but wrote that \"after seeing ''The Interview'' and the ruckus its mere existence has caused, the only sensible reaction is amazement at the huge disconnect between the innocuousness of the film and the viciousness of the response.\"<ref name=\"hale\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|title=Memo to Kim Jong-un: Dying Is Easy, Comedy Is Hard|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220053144/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Political response===\nIn the wake of the Sony Pictures Entertainment hack, leaks revealed e-mails between Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO Michael Lynton and [[RAND Corporation]] defense analyst Bruce Bennett from June 2014. Bennett advised against toning down ''The Interview''{{-'}}s graphic Jong-un death scene, in the hope that it would \"start some real thinking in South Korea and, I believe, in the North once the DVD leaks into the North\". Bennett expressed his view that \"the only resolution I can see to the North Korean nuclear and other threats is for the North Korean government to eventually go away\", which he felt would be likeliest to occur following an assassination of Kim. Lynton replied that a senior figure in the [[United States Department of State]] agreed. Bennett responded that the office of [[Robert R. King]], U.S. Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, had determined that the North Korean statements had been \"typical North Korean bullying, likely without follow-up\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive: Sony Emails Say State Department Blessed Kim Jong-Un Assassination in 'The Interview'|first=William|last=Boot|work=The Daily Beast|date=December 17, 2014|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217180144/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[CNN]], Bennett said Lynton sits on the board of trustees of the RAND Corporation, which had asked Bennett to talk to Lynton and give his opinion on the film.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |title=Expert on N. Korea on 'The Interview' |date=December 19, 2014 |publisher=CNN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223202708/http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |archivedate=December 23, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Bennett felt ''The Interview'' was \"coarse\" and \"over the top\", but that \"the depiction of Kim Jong-un was a picture that needed to get into North Korea. There are a lot of people in prison camps in North Korea who need to take advantage of a change of thinking in the north.\" Bennett felt that if the DVD were smuggled into the country it might have an effect \"over time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|title='The Interview' Release Would Have Damaged Kim Jong Un Internally, Says Rand Expert Who Saw Movie At Sony's Request|date=December 19, 2014|work=Yahoo Movies UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223211521/https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bennett contacted the Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, a personal friend of his, who \"took the standard government approach: we don't tell industry what to do\".<ref name=\"cnn.com\" /> [[Jen Psaki]], a spokesperson for the United States Department of State, confirmed that [[Daniel R. Russel]], the U.S. [[Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs]], had spoken to Sony executives; she reiterated that \"entertainers are free to make movies of their choosing, and we are not involved in that\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2014/12/235370.htm#DEPARTMENT|title=Daily Press Briefing - December 17, 2014|work=U.S. Department of State|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn [[Greece]], in April 2017, the film's opening scene, depicting a young girl reciting a poem with hate speech, was mistakenly broadcast in the news bulletin of [[Alpha TV]] and the [[news program]] ''Live News'' on [[Open TV|Epsilon TV]], as a real-life provocative event against the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepressproject.gr/article/110363/O-Euaggelatos-parousiazei-skini-satirikis-tainias-gia-ti-BKorea-os-pragmatiki-video|title=\u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 Alpha \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c3\u03ba\u03b7\u03bd\u03ae \u03ba\u03c9\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392.\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1 \u03c9\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae|trans-title=Evangelatos and Alpha present scene of a comedy film about North Korea as a real-life event|language=Greek|website=The Press Project|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref> In response to the backlash on various [[online newspaper]]s, Antonis Sroiter and Nikos Evangelatos, the hosts of the said programs, apologized in posts they made on their social accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topontiki.gr/article/217430/o-nikos-eyaggelatos-zita-syggnomi-gia-tin-gkafa-kaname-lathos|title=\u039f \u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b6\u03b7\u03c4\u03ac \u03c3\u03c5\u03b3\u03b3\u03bd\u03ce\u03bc\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b3\u03ba\u03ac\u03c6\u03b1: \u039a\u03ac\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5 \u03bb\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2|trans-title=Nikos Evangelatos apologizes for the blunder: We made a mistake|language=Greek|website=[[To Pontiki]]|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eleftherostypos.gr/perierga/94235-i-apologia-sroiter-gia-to-reportaz-me-to-koritsaki-apo-ti-boreia-korea/|title=\u0397\u2026 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03b1 \u03a3\u03c1\u03cc\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c1\u03b5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03ac\u03b6 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1|trans-title=Sroiter's... apology for the reportage with the girl from North Korea|language=Greek|website=[[Eleftheros Typos]]|date=2017-04-22|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Freedom of speech|North Korea}}\n* [[Assassinations in fiction]]\n* [[List of films set in or about North Korea]]\n* ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', another comedy film satirizing North Korea\n* ''[[The Dictator (2012 film)|The Dictator]]'', a comedy film satirizing [[Middle East|Middle Eastern]] dictators\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.seetheinterview.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2788710|The Interview}}\n* {{mojo title|interview2014|The Interview}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_interview_2014|The Interview}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-interview|The Interview}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interview, The (2014 film)}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2014 controversies]]\n[[Category:2010s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy films]] \n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s satirical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]] \n[[Category:American political comedy films]]\n[[Category:American political satire films]]\n[[Category:Fiction about assassinations]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Point Grey Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Kim Jong-un]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Events relating to freedom of expression]]\n[[Category:Korean-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Henry Jackman]]\n[[Category:Films about assassinations]]\n[[Category:Films about the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Evan Goldberg]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n[[Category:Films set in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films set in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:North Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Self-censorship]]\n[[Category:Works banned in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2014 film directed by Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg}}\n{{about|the 2014 film||Interview (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Interview\n| image          = The Interview 2014 poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster{{efn|The [[Korean language|Korean]] text translates as: \"The war will begin\" (on the missiles and tanks). The Korean text line right beneath the stars' names above the movie title translates to: \"Please do not believe these ignorant dishonorable Americans!\" while the small text to the left and right of the title, meanwhile, translates to the film's title. The fine print at the bottom of the poster reiterates the opening tagline from the top of the poster, translating to: \"Awful work by the 'pigs' that created ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'' and ''[[This Is the End]]''{{-\"}}.<ref>Vary, Adam B. (June 11, 2014). [https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill#.nq6r90dzZ3 \"The Poster For Seth Rogen and James Franco's New Comedy Is Filled with Anti-American Propaganda\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328132022/http://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-poster-for-the-new-seth-rogenjames-franco-comedy-is-fill |date=March 28, 2016 }}. [[BuzzFeed]]. Retrieved December 21, 2014.</ref>}}\n| director       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Evan Goldberg]]\n}}\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* James Weaver\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Dan Sterling]]\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Seth Rogen\n* Evan Goldberg\n* Dan Sterling\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Franco]]\n* [[Seth Rogen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Randall Park]]\n<!--per billing block-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Henry Jackman]]\n| cinematography = [[Brandon Trost]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Zene Baker]]\n* Evan Henke\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Point Grey Pictures]]\n* [[LStar Capital]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]{{efn|All references to [[Sony Pictures]] were removed from the final film and marketing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Matt |title=Hack Attack: Sony Orders Its Name Removed from \u2018Interview\u2019 Marketing Materials |url=https://www.thewrap.com/hack-attack-sony-orders-its-name-removed-from-interview-marketing-materials/ |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=December 12, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|12|11|Los Angeles|2014|12|24|United States<!--- This is for the on demand date, and the film was only released on December 24. Please go to the talk page before changing this --->}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 111:49 --><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | title=''The Interview'' (15) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 17, 2014 | accessdate=November 17, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129045957/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/interview-film | archivedate=November 29, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Korean\n}}\n| budget         = $44 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|title=Sony Weighing Premium VOD Release for 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 17, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=January 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116144807/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-weighing-premium-vod-release-for-the-interview-exclusive-1201381920/|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|title=Sony Could Lose $75 Million on 'The Interview' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=December 18, 2014|work=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220194759/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-could-lose-75-million-on-the-interview-exclusive-1201382506/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = $12.3 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | title = The Interview (2014) \u2013 Financial Information | work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = May 1, 2019  | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180422062312/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The | archivedate = April 22, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Interview''''' is a 2014 American [[action comedy film]] co-produced and directed by [[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] in their second directorial work, following ''[[This Is the End]]'' (2013). The screenplay was written by [[Dan Sterling]], based on a story he co-wrote with Rogen and Goldberg. The film stars Rogen and [[James Franco]] as journalists who set up an interview with [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ([[Randall Park]]), and are then recruited by the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] to assassinate him. The film is heavily inspired by a 2012 ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' documentary.\n\nRogen and Goldberg developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, with [[Kim Jong-il]] as the original assassination target. In 2011, after [[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|Jong-il's death]] and Jong-un's succession as the [[List of heads of state of North Korea|North Korean leader]], Rogen and Goldberg redeveloped the script with the focus on Jong-un's character. ''The Interview'' was first announced in March 2013, at the beginning of pre-production. [[Principal photography]] was in [[Vancouver]] from October to December 2013. The film was produced by [[Columbia Pictures]], [[LStar Capital]] and Rogen and Goldberg's [[Point Grey Pictures]], and distributed by [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]].\n\nIn June 2014, the North Korean government threatened action against the United States if Sony released the film. As a result, Sony delayed the release from October to December and reportedly re-edited the film to make it more acceptable to North Korea. In November, the computer systems of Sony were [[Sony Pictures hack|hacked]] by the \"Guardians of Peace\", a group the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] claimed has ties to North Korea.<ref>[[Gabi Siboni]] and David Siman-Tov, [http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf Cyberspace Extortion: North Korea versus the United States] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820031432/http://www.inss.org.il/uploadImages/systemFiles/No.%20646%20-%20Gabi%20and%20Dudi%20for%20web.pdf |date=August 20, 2016 }}, [[Institute for National Security Studies (Israel)|INSS]] Insight No. 646, December 23, 2014.</ref> The group also threatened terrorist attacks against theaters showing the film. As a result, major theater chains opted not to release the film, and Sony instead released it for online digital rental and purchase on December 24, 2014, followed by a [[limited release]] at selected theaters the next day.\n\nIn December 2014, [[South Korea|South Korean]] singer [[Yoon Mi-rae]] revealed that the film used her song \"Pay Day\" without permission, and that she was taking legal action.<ref name=\"newsmp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.soompi.com/2014/12/26/yoon-mi-rae-to-take-legal-action-against-sony-pictures-for-using-her-song-in-the-interview-without-permission/|title=Yoon Mi Rae to Take Legal Action against Sony Pictures for Using Her Song in \"The Interview\" without Permission|date=27 December 2014|work=Soompi|author=|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> Yoon Mi-rae and her label [[Feel Ghood Music]] reached a settlement with Sony Pictures Entertainment on the 13th of May 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/201343/20150517/sony-the-interview-yoon-mi-rae-payday.htm|title=Sony And Yoon Mi Rae Reach Settlement Over Unlicensed Song Usage In 'The Interview'|website=KpopStarz|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> \n\n''The Interview'' grossed $40 million in digital rentals, making it Sony's most successful digital release and earned an additional $12.3 million worldwide in box office ticket sales on a $44 million budget. It received mixed reviews for its humor and subject matter, although a few critics praised the performances of Rogen, Franco, Park and [[Diana Bang]].\n\n==Plot==\nDave Skylark is the host of the [[talk show]] ''Skylark Tonight'', where he interviews various celebrities about personal topics and gossip. After Skylark and his crew celebrate their producer Aaron Rapaport's 1,000th episode, Rapaport is upset by a producer peer who criticized the show as not being a real news program. Rapaport reveals his concern and urge for change, to which Skylark agrees. Later, Skylark discovers that [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Jong-un]] is a fan of ''Skylark Tonight'', prompting Rapaport to arrange an interview for him. Rapaport travels to a place outside [[Dandong]], [[China]] to receive instructions from Sook-yin Park, the [[Propaganda in North Korea|North Korean chief propagandist]], and Rapaport accepts the task of interviewing Kim on behalf of Skylark.\n\nThe next day, [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent Lacey shows up at Skylark and Rapaport's place, proposing that the duo assassinate Kim using a [[Transdermal patch|transdermal strip]] that will expose Kim to [[ricin]] via handshake; they reluctantly agree. Skylark carries the ricin strip hidden inside a pack of gum. Upon their arrival in the [[Residences of North Korean leaders|presidential palace]] in [[Pyongyang]], they are introduced to security officers Koh and Yu; Koh discovers the strip and chews it, believing it to be gum. That night, Lacey airdrops them two more strips from a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]], but in order to smuggle it back to their room, Rapaport has to evade a [[Siberian tiger]] and then hide the container in his rectum. Later, Kim shows up and introduces himself to Skylark.\n\nSkylark spends the day with Kim by playing [[basketball]], hanging out and partying together. Kim persuades Skylark that he is misunderstood as both a cruel dictator and a failed administrator, and they become friends. At dinner, Koh has a [[Epileptic seizure|seizure]] due to the ricin poisoning and accidentally shoots Yu before dying. The next morning, Skylark feels guilty and discards one of the ricin strips, then thwarts Rapaport's attempt to poison Kim with the second strip. After another dinner mourning the death of Kim's bodyguards, Skylark witnesses Kim's malicious side as he [[Korean conflict|threatens war]] against [[South Korea]] and \"every single enemy of his country\". Skylark leaves and after taking a walk, he discovers that a nearby grocery store is merely [[Potemkin village|fake]] and realizes that Kim has been lying to him. At the same time, during an attempted sex with Rapaport (who still has the ricin strip in his hand), Sook-yin reveals that she despises Kim and apologizes for defending the regime. Skylark, Rapaport and Sook-yin plan to ruin [[Kim Jong-un's cult of personality|Kim's cult of personality]] by causing him to cry on air. Before the broadcast starts, Kim gives Skylark a puppy as a gift to keep.\n\nDuring the internationally televised interview with Kim, Skylark addresses increasingly sensitive topics (including the country's [[North Korean famine|food shortage]] issues and [[Sanctions against North Korea|economic sanctions]] imposed by the US) and challenges Kim's need for [[Kim Jong-il|his father]]'s approval. Meanwhile, Sook-yin and Rapaport seize control of the broadcasting center and attack guards trying to cut off the broadcast. Despite his initial resistance, Kim eventually cries uncontrollably and soils himself after Skylark sings [[Firework (song)|\"Firework\"]] by [[Katy Perry]] (having learned of Kim's fondness of Perry earlier), ruining his reputation. Feeling betrayed and labeling Skylark as a \"fake friend\", Kim shoots him and leaves, but Skylark survives due to a [[bulletproof vest]]. Skylark, Rapaport and Sook-yin regroup (with the puppy in tow) and escape the presidential palace with the unexpected help of a panel-control guard. The trio hijack Kim's [[T-54/T-55|personal tank]], originally given to [[Kim Il-sung]] by [[Joseph Stalin]], to get to their pickup point. Kim boards a helicopter while his own army attacks the group. He prepares a nuclear missile launch, but before he can issue the command to launch, Skylark shoots down Kim's helicopter, killing him. \n\nWith the immediate threat over, Sook guides Skylark and Rapaport to an escape route where they are rescued and loaded onto a rescue craft by three [[SEAL Team Six]] members disguised as [[Korean People's Army]] troops, while Sook goes to [[Pyongyang]] to ensure political stability. Back in the United States, Skylark writes a book about his experience while North Korea become [[denuclearization|denuclearized]] and [[democratization|democratized]] under Sook-yin, who steps in as an [[Transitional government|interim]] leader.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Franco]] as Dave Skylark\n* [[Seth Rogen]] as Aaron Rapaport\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as Agent Lacey\n* [[Randall Park]] as [[Kim Jong-un]]\n* [[Diana Bang]] as Sook-yin Park\n* [[Timothy Simons]] as Malcolm\n<!-- these are listed after the main six in the longer closing credits -->\n* Reese Alexander as Agent Botwin\n* [[Anders Holm]] as Jake\n* [[Charles Chun|Charles Rahi Chun]] as General Jong\n* [[Ben Schwartz]] as Daryl\n<!-- ones listed after here were minor characters such as Two-Fingered Man, Train Passengers, Korean Girl, Hot Korean Girls, Drone Pilot, etc. -->\n\nThe film also features [[cameo appearance]]s from [[Eminem]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Bill Maher]], [[Seth Meyers]], [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]], [[Brian Williams]] and [[Scott Pelley]]. [[Iggy Azalea]], [[Nicki Minaj]], [[Emma Stone]], [[Zac Efron]] and [[Guy Fieri]] appear in the title graphic card for ''Skylark Tonight''.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]] developed the idea for ''The Interview'' in the late 2000s, joking about what would happen if a journalist was required to assassinate a world leader.<ref name=\"December2014RS\">{{cite journal| first =Josh| last =Eells| date =December 17, 2014| title =Seth Rogen at the Crossroads| journal =[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]| issue =1224/1225| pages =52\u201357; 86| location =[[New York City]]| issn =0035-791X| url =https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| accessdate =December 17, 2014| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141225013015/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/seth-rogen-interview-north-korea-controversy-cover-story-20141217?page=4| archivedate =December 25, 2014| df =mdy-all}}</ref>\nInitially, screenwriter [[Dan Sterling]] wrote his script involving a fictional dictator from a fictional country, but Rogen, Goldberg and Sony executives asked him to rewrite the script focusing on Kim.<ref name=\"Maroff\">{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|title=The Interview: an \"Act of War\"|last=Maroff|first=Melissa|date=December 18, 2014|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|accessdate=July 21, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150721111520/http://creativescreenwriting.com/the-interview-an-act-of-war/|archivedate=July 21, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The screenplay was then titled ''Kill Kim Jong Un''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weinstein|first1=Shelli|title=Seth Rogen: Censoring North Korea in 'The Interview' 'Seemed Wrong'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|accessdate=February 6, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 4, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205115351/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/seth-rogen-censoring-north-korea-in-the-interview-seemed-wrong-1201424038/|archivedate=February 5, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Previous iterations of the story revolved around [[Kim Jong-il]], but put the project on hold until Jong-il died and his son [[Kim Jong-un]] assumed power in 2011. Development resumed when Rogen and Goldberg realized that Jong-un is closer to their own age, which they felt would be more humorous. To write the story, co-written with ''[[Daily Show]]'' writer [[Dan Sterling]], they researched meticulously by reading non-fiction books and watching video footage about North Korea. The script was later reviewed by an employee in the [[United States Department of State|State Department]].<ref name=Jan2015NewYorker>{{cite news|last1=Demick|first1=Barbara|title=A North Korea Watcher Watches \"The Interview\"|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|accessdate=July 7, 2015|work=newyorker.com|date=January 2, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714153529/http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/north-korea-watcher-watches-interview|archivedate=July 14, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg aimed to make the project more relevant and satirical than their previous films while retaining [[toilet humor]].<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> They were pleased when former [[NBA]] star [[Dennis Rodman]] visited North Korea, as it reinforced their belief that the premise of the film was realistic.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-production===\nIn March 2013, it was announced that Rogen and Goldberg would direct a comedy film for [[Columbia Pictures]] in which Rogen would star alongside [[James Franco]], with Franco playing a talk-show host and Rogen playing his producer.<ref name=March2013THR>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Seth Rogen to Direct, Star in 'The Interview' for Columbia Pictures (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=March 21, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613020954/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-direct-star-interview-430224|archivedate=June 13, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rogen and Goldberg were on board to produce along with James Weaver through [[Point Grey Pictures]], while Columbia was said to finance the $30 million budgeted film.<ref name=\"March2013THR\" /> [[Lizzy Caplan]] joined the film's cast in October 2013. Caplan signed on to play Agent Lacey, a CIA agent who tries to get Franco's character to assassinate the Korean prime minister.<ref name=October2013THR>{{cite news|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Lizzy Caplan Joins Seth Rogen and James Franco in 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232251/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lizzy-caplan-joins-seth-rogen-640065|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Randall Park]] and [[Timothy Simons]] signed on to co-star later that month. Park plays the North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-Un]] and Simons the director of the talk show.<ref name=October2013THR1>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Randall Park and 'Veep's' Timothy Simons to Co-Star in Seth Rogen's 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|accessdate=July 6, 2015|work=hollywoodreporter.com|date=October 8, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420010237/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/randall-park-veeps-timothy-simons-645166|archivedate=April 20, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | title=North Korea Calls Seth Rogen-James Franco Film An 'Act Of War' | work=The Huffington Post | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | author=Mazza, Ed | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627132111/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/25/north-korea-seth-rogen-james-franco_n_5528386.html | archivedate=June 27, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Park was the first to audition for the role of Kim and got the part immediately.  Before filming began, Park gained 15 pounds and shaved his head to resemble Jong-un's [[crew cut]].  His role was praised by critics.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /><ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /> Although Rogen and Goldberg wrote the character of Kim as \"robotic and strict\", Park instead played it \"sheepish and shy\", which they found more humorous.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> [[Diana Bang]] was cast as Sook-yin Park, for which she was well received by critics.<ref name=\"ScottFoundasVariety\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |title=''The Interview'' Actress Diana Bang Is Ready for Anything |author=Smith, Krista |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 20, 2014 |accessdate=December 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217174628/http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/11/diana-bang-the-interview-photos |archivedate=December 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], on October 10, 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last=Schaefer|first=Glen|title=Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg come home to shoot B.C. for Korea in The Interview|url=http://blogs.theprovince.com/2013/10/12/seth-rogen-and-evan-goldberg-come-home-to-shoot-b-c-for-korea-in-the-interview/|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Province|date=October 12, 2013}}</ref> and concluded on December 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Seth Rogen, Evan Goldberg to Direct 'The Interview' in Vancouver|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|accessdate=December 25, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 30, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232252/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/seth-rogen-evan-goldberg-direct-639082|archivedate=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> There are hundreds of visual effects in the film;  a crowd scene at the Pyongyang airport, for example, was digitally manipulated with a shot from ''[[22 Jump Street]]''.<ref name=\"December2014RS\" />\n\n===Pre-release reaction===\nIn June 2014, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that the film had \"touched a nerve\" within the North Korean government, as they are \"notoriously paranoid about perceived threats to their safety.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title=North Korea threatens 'merciless' response over Seth Rogen film|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|work=The Guardian|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418173750/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/25/north-korea-merciless-response-us-kim-jong-un-film|archivedate=April 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianBranigan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|title=Sony's cancellation of ''The Interview'' surprises North Korea-watchers|last=Branigan|first=Tanya|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220190356/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/sony-cancellation-the-interview-hack-north-korea-watchers|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Korean Central News Agency]] (KCNA), the state news agency of North Korea, reported that their government  promised \"stern\" and \"merciless\" retaliation if the film was released. KCNA said that the release of a film portraying the assassination of the North Korean leader would not be allowed and it would be considered the \"most blatant act of terrorism and war.\"<ref name=\"North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war'\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | title=North Korea calls new Seth Rogen film, The Interview, an 'act of war' | publisher=CBC News | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=June 26, 2014 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626045743/http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/north-korea-calls-new-seth-rogen-film-the-interview-an-act-of-war-1.2686677 | archivedate=June 26, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea threatens war on US over Kim Jong-un movie|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|accessdate=June 25, 2014|publisher=BBC|date=June 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625140625/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28014069|archivedate=June 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The next month, North Korea's [[Permanent Representative to the United Nations|United Nations ambassador]] Ja Song-nam condemned the film, describing its production and distribution as \"an act of war\" and because of Kim's assassination in the film, \"the most undisguised sponsoring of terrorism.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\">{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |title=North Korea complains to UN about Seth Rogen comedy The Interview |work=The Guardian |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 30, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730031714/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/north-korea-un-the-interview-seth-rogen-james-franco |archivedate=July 30, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''The Guardian''  described Song-nam's comments as \"perfect publicity for the movie.\"<ref name=\"GuardianBen\" /> Later in July, KCNA wrote to U.S. President [[Barack Obama]], asking to have the film pulled.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Julian|title=North Korea appeals to White House to halt release of US comedy film|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=July 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812122012/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10973720/North-Korea-appeals-to-White-House-to-halt-release-of-US-comedy-film.html|archivedate=August 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Shortly before the planned release of the film on December 25, 2014, screenwriter Dan Sterling told ''Creative Screenwriting:'' \"I couldn't believe that the most infamous man in the world knew about my script \u2013 but most importantly, I would never want something I wrote to lead to some kind of humanitarian disaster. I would be horrified if anyone got hurt over this.\"<ref name=\"Maroff\"/>\n\n==Release==\n===Delay and changes===\nIn August 2014, Sony delayed the film's release from October 10 to December 25, 2014.<ref name=\"release\">{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' with Seth Rogen, James Franco Pushed Back to Christmas|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|accessdate=August 7, 2014|work=Variety|date=August 7, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810035632/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-delayed-release-date-1201277869/|archivedate=August 10, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Sony made post-production alterations to the film to modify its portrayal of North Korea, including modifying the designs of buttons worn by characters, originally modeled after real North Korean military buttons praising the country's leaders, and cutting a portion of Kim Jong-un's death scene.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Tatiana|title=Sony Altering Kim Jong Un Assassination Film 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|accessdate=August 14, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 13, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815064109/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-altering-kim-jong-assassination-725092|archivedate=August 15, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sony Pictures Entertainment hack and threats===\n{{main|Sony Pictures hack}}\n[[File:Sony Pictures Entertainment entrance 1.jpg|right|thumb|A hacker group compromised much of Sony Pictures Entertainment's computer system in late 2014 in retaliation for the film's content.]]\nOn November 24, 2014, an anonymous group identifying themselves as the \"Guardians of Peace\" hacked the computer networks of Columbia Pictures's parent company Sony Pictures Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sanger|first1=David E.|last2=Perlroth|first2=Nicole|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|title=U.S. Said to Find North Korea Ordered Cyberattack on Sony|work=The New York Times|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218130909/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?&_r=0|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The hackers [[Internet leak|leaked]] internal emails, employee records and several recent and unreleased Sony Pictures films, including ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'', ''[[Mr. Turner (film)|Mr. Turner]]'', ''[[Still Alice]]'', and ''[[To Write Love on Her Arms (film)|To Write Love on Her Arms]]''. The North Korean government denied involvement in the hack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|title=North Korea denies hacking Sony Pictures|first=Justin|last=McCurry|work=The Guardian|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218083138/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/04/north-korea-denies-hacking-sony-pictures-cyber-attack-movies|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\">{{cite news|title=Hackers who targeted Sony invoke 9/11 attacks in warning to moviegoers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|accessdate=December 17, 2014|work=The Guardian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217042527/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/16/employees-sue-failure-guard-personal-data-leaked-hackers|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sony's New Movies Leak Online Following Hack Attack|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|website=NBC News|accessdate=December 1, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202203232/http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/sonys-new-movies-leak-online-following-hack-attack-n258511|archivedate=December 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 8, the hackers leaked further materials, including a demand that Sony pull \"the movie of terrorism\", widely interpreted as referring to ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hackers told Sony to pull 'The Interview'|first=Elizabeth|last=Weise|work=USA Today|date=December 9, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130004703/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/12/08/sony-hack-the-interview/20110609/|archivedate=November 30, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korean Government Thought To Be Behind Sony Pictures Hack|date=December 1, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424234518/http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/12/01/367838950/north-korean-government-thought-to-be-behind-sony-pictures-hack|archivedate=April 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea's Cyber Skills Get Attention Amid Sony Hacking Mystery|date=December 4, 2014|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|publisher=NPR|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407195600/http://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2014/12/04/368449855/north-koreas-cyber-skills-get-attention-amid-sony-hacking-mystery|archivedate=April 7, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2014, the hackers threatened to attack the [[New York City|New York]] premiere of ''The Interview'' and any cinema showing the film.<ref name=\"guardian-invoke911\" /> Two further messages were released on December 1; one, sent in a private message to Sony executives, said that the hackers would not release further information if Sony never released the film and removed it from the internet. The other, posted to [[Pastebin]], a web application used for text storage which the Guardians of Peace had used for previous messages, stated that Sony had \"suffered enough\" and could release ''The Interview'', but only if Kim Jong-un's death scene was not \"too happy\". The message also threatened that if Sony made another film antagonizing North Korea, the hackers \"will be here ready to fight\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weise |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Johnson |first2=Kevin |title=Obama: Sony \"did the wrong thing\" when it pulled movie |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=December 19, 2014 |accessdate=December 19, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219204906/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ |archivedate=December 19, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Distribution===\n''The Interview'' was not released in Japan, as live-action comedy films do not often perform well in the market. In the Asia-Pacific region, it was released only in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|title='The Interview' to Have Only Limited Release in Asia|date=December 10, 2014|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last1=Schilling|first1=Mark|accessdate=December 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213194607/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-interview-to-have-only-limited-release-in-asia-1201376806/|archivedate=December 13, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nRogen predicted that the film would make its way to North Korea, stating that \"we were told one of the reasons they're so against the movie is that they're afraid it'll actually get into North Korea. They do have [[Bootleg recording|bootlegs]] and stuff. Maybe the tapes will make their way to North Korea and cause a revolution.\"<ref name=\"December2014RS\" /> ''[[Business Insider]]'' reported via [[Free North Korea Radio]] that there was high demand for bootleg copies of the film in North Korea.<ref name=\"BI\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Eugene|title=Demand For 'The Interview' Is Shooting Up In North Korea And Its Government Is Freaking Out|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|website=Business Insider|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229032411/http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korean-demand-for-the-interview-2014-12|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The South Korean [[human rights organization]]s [[Fighters for a Free North Korea]] and [[Human Rights Foundation]], largely made up of North Korean defectors, planned to distribute DVD copies of ''The Interview'' [[Balloon campaigns in Korea|via balloon drops]].<ref name=\"hr20141216\">{{cite news|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 16, 2014|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|title=Sony Hack: Activists to Drop 'Interview' DVDs Over North Korea Via Balloon|first=Paul|last=Bond|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217073943/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-hack-activists-drop-interview-758529|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|title=Launching Balloons into North Korea: Propaganda Over Pyongyang|date=18 March 2015|work=VICE news|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402162347/https://news.vice.com/video/launching-balloons-into-north-korea-propaganda-over-pyongyang|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The groups had previously air-dropped offline copies of the [[Korean Wikipedia]] into North Korea on a [[bootable USB]] memory device.<ref name=\"cnn20141218\">{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|title=Activists plan to drop 'Interview' DVDs in North Korea|last=Segall|first=Laurie|publisher=CNN|authorlink=Laurie Segall|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=December 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220202241/http://money.cnn.com/2014/12/18/technology/north-korea-interview-drop-sony/|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The balloon drop was scrapped after the North Korean government referred to the plan as a [[de facto]] \"declaration of war.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|title=South Korean activists postpone sending of copies of The Interview to North Korea by balloon|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=24 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323214646/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-23/south-korea-activists-postpone-the-interview-dvd-balloon-protest/6342314|archivedate=March 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|title=North Korea Calls Planned Balloon Drop of 'The Interview' DVDs a 'De Facto Declaration of War'|first=Gillian|last=Mohney|date=23 March 2015|work=VICE News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094846/https://news.vice.com/article/north-korea-calls-planned-balloon-drop-of-the-interview-dvds-a-de-facto-declaration-of-war|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation of wide theatrical release===\nThe [[Film premiere|premiere]] was held in [[Los Angeles]] on December 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|title='The Interview' Premiere: Seth Rogen Thanks Amy Pascal \"For Having The Balls to Make This Movie\"|first=Tim|last=Appelo|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217202418/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-premiere-seth-rogen-thanks-756765|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film scheduled a [[wide release]] in the UK and Ireland on February 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | title = 'The Interview' To Get Wide Release In The UK | first = Ali | last = Jaafar | publisher = Deadline.com | date = January 7, 2015 | accessdate = January 12, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150110034332/http://deadline.com/2015/01/the-interview-wide-release-uk-1201342935/ | archivedate = January 10, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Following the hackers' threats on December 16, Rogen and Franco canceled scheduled publicity appearances and Sony pulled all television advertising.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|title=Seth Rogen and James Franco Cancel All Media Appearances for 'The Interview'|work=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216230918/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/seth-rogen-and-james-franco-cancel-all-media-appearances-for-the-interview-1201380917/|archivedate=December 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] said that they would not object to cinema owners delaying the film to ensure the safety of filmgoers. Shortly afterwards, the [[ArcLight Hollywood|ArcLight]] and [[Carmike Cinemas|Carmike]] cinema chains announced that they would not screen the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|title=First Theaters Cancel 'The Interview' After Hacker Threats|first1=Jen|last1=Yamato|first2=Dominic|last2=Patten|work=Deadline|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217055402/http://deadline.com/2014/12/sony-theater-owners-pull-the-interview-terror-threats-1201327612/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, Sony canceled the New York City premiere. Later that day, other major theater chains including [[AMC Theatres|AMC]], [[Cinemark Theatres|Cinemark]], [[Cineplex Entertainment|Cineplex]], [[Regal Entertainment Group|Regal]] and [[Southern Theatres]] either delayed or canceled screenings of the film.<ref name=\"variety-interviewdropped\">{{cite web|title=Major U.S. Theaters Drop 'The Interview' After Sony Hacker Threats|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141217061335/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/major-u-s-theaters-drop-the-interview-after-sony-hacker-threats-1201381861/|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The chains reportedly came under pressure from [[shopping mall]]s where many theaters are located, which feared that the terror threat would ruin their holiday sales. They also feared expensive lawsuits in the event of an attack; Cinemark, for instance, contended that it could not have foreseen the [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting]], which took place at one of its multiplexes, a defense that would not hold in the event of an attack at a screening of ''The Interview''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|title=Sony Drops 'The Interview' Following Terrorist Threats|first1=Brooks|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael|last2=Cieply|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129055352/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/business/sony-the-interview-threats.html|archivedate=January 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe cancellation also affected other films in which each films' subject matter is North Korea. An [[Alamo Drafthouse Cinema]] location in [[Dallas]] planned to hold a free screening of ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', which satirizes Kim Jong-un's father [[Kim Jong-il]], in place of its previously scheduled screening of ''The Interview'';<ref name=\"thr-tawp\">{{cite web|title=Texas Theater to Show 'Team America' In Place of 'The Interview'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218054150/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/texas-theater-show-team-america-759037|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"variety-tawpdallas\">{{cite web|title='Team America: World Police' Replaces 'The Interview' at Dallas Theater|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218051139/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/team-america-world-police-replaces-the-interview-at-dallas-theater-1201382348/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Paramount Pictures]] refused to permit the screening.<ref name=\"deadline-tawpcancelled\">{{cite web|title=Paramount Cancels 'Team America' Showings, Theaters Say|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218215711/https://deadline.com/2014/12/paramount-cancel-team-america-1201329597/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[New Regency]] pulled out of a planned film adaptation of the graphic novel ''[[Pyongyang: A Journey in North Korea|Pyongyang]]'' starring [[Steve Carell]]; Carell declared it a \"sad day for creative expression\".<ref name=\"cbc-carellcancelled\">{{cite news|title=Steve Carell's North Korea movie from Guy Delisle novel scrapped after Sony hack|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|website=CBC News|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219202505/http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/steve-carell-s-north-korea-movie-from-guy-delisle-novel-scrapped-after-sony-hack-1.2877462|archivedate=December 19, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony received criticism for canceling the wide release.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last1=Sinha-Roy|first1=Piya|title=Hollywood slams Sony, movie theaters for canceling 'The Interview'|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|agency=Reuters|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211630/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/18/us-sony-cybersecurity-hollywood-idUSKBN0JW08W20141218|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcus|first1=Stephanie|title=Celebrities React To Sony Canceling 'The Interview' Release|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=December 17, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218111029/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/celebrities-react-the-interview-canceled_n_6344232.html|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|title=Hollywood Hits Twitter To Vent Anger About 'The Interview' Being Pulled|work=Deadline|date=December 17, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218045202/http://deadline.com/2014/12/hollywood-reaction-the-interview-pulled-twitter-1201328894/|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Guardian'' film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]] wrote that it was an \"unprecedented defeat on American turf\", but that \"North Korea will find that their bullying edict will haunt them.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Peter|title=The Interview: Sony's retreat signals an unprecedented defeat on American turf|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|work=The Guardian|date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219171059/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/18/the-interview-sony-hack-north-korea-film|archivedate=December 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''In the Capital'' and [[Gizmodo]] suggested the cancellation caused a [[Streisand effect]], whereby the attempt to remove or censor a work has the unintended consequence of publicizing it more widely.<ref name=\"itc20141215\">{{cite news |last1=Schwartz |first1=Eric Hal |title=Sony Pictures Is in for a Lesson on the Streisand Effect |url=http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |accessdate=December 20, 2014 |work=In The Capital |date=December 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218174836/http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/12/15/sony-pictures-streisand-effect-media-delete-hacked-data/ |archivedate=December 18, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |title=The Streisand Effect and Why We All Now Want to See 'The Interview' |publisher=Gizmodo.co.uk |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227120034/http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2014/12/the-streisand-effect-and-why-we-all-now-want-to-see-the-interview/ |archivedate=December 27, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a press conference, U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] said that though he was sympathetic to Sony's need to protect employees, he thought Sony had \"made a mistake. We cannot have a society in which some dictator in some place can start imposing censorship in the United States. I wish they'd spoken to me first. I would have told them: do not get into the pattern in which you are intimidated.\"<ref name=\"obama\">{{cite news|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/obama-sony-made-mistake-canceling-film-release/story?id=27720800|title=Sony Hacking: President Obama Says Company Made 'Mistake' in Canceling 'The Interview'|first1=Devin|last1=Dwyer |first2=Mary|last2=Bruce|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO [[Michael Lynton]], the cancellation of the wide release was a response to the refusal of cinema chains to screen the film, not the hackers' threats, and that Sony would seek other ways to distribute the film. Sony released a statement saying that the company \"is and always has been strongly committed to the First Amendment ... Free expression should never be suppressed by threats and extortion.\"<ref name=\"hrdec19\" />\n\nThe movie was not released in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbth.com/arts/327422-banned-movies-russia|title=Final cut: Movies that have been banned in Russia|last=Tokmasheva|first=Maria|date=2018-01-30|website=www.rbth.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n===Revised release===\nAfter the wide release cancellation, Sony considered other ways to release the film, citing pressure from the film industry, theater owners, and the White House.<ref name=\"hrdec19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|title=Sony Fires Back at Obama: \"We Had No Choice\" But to Cancel 'The Interview' Release|first1=Tatiana|last1=Siegel|first2=Erik|last2=Hayden|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224170752/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-fires-back-at-obama-759553|archivedate=December 24, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"whitehouseofficialinterviewresponsenbc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|title=Obama: Sony 'Made a Mistake' By Pulling 'The Interview' Movie|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=April 3, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403013318/http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sony-hack/obama-sony-made-mistake-pulling-interview-movie-n271786|archivedate=April 3, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DecPressure\">{{cite news|last1=Atkinson|first1=Claire|title=Sony faces pressure to release 'The Interview'|url=https://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=New York Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223122056/http://nypost.com/2014/12/23/sony-faces-pressure-to-release-the-interview/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[NBC News|NBC]]'s ''[[Meet the Press]]'' on December 21, Sony's legal counsel [[David Boies]] noted that the company was still committed to releasing the film.<ref name=\"DecPressure\" /> Sony planned a  [[limited release]] for December 25, 2014, at more than three hundred American independent and [[arthouse cinema]]s.<ref>Shaw, Lucas (December 23, 2014). [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html \"Sony to Release ''The Interview'' in More Than 300 Theaters on Christmas Day\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225220539/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-12-23/sony-to-release-the-interview-on-dec-25-theaters-say.html |date=December 25, 2014 }}. ''[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]''. Retrieved December 26, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\" /><ref name=\"dp20141223\" /><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ 'Hobbit' rules box office, 'Interview' succeeds online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916012041/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/12/28/box-office-the-hobbit-interview/20965787/ |date=September 16, 2017 }}. ''USA Today''. Retrieved December 29, 2014.</ref> Lynton stated that Sony was trying to show the film to the largest audience by securing as many theaters as they could.<ref name=\"deadline-limitedrelease\">{{cite web|title='The Interview' Release Back On For Christmas Day \u2013 Update|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223224802/https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-release-back-on-christmas-sony-attack-1201334389/|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"dp20141223\">{{cite web|last=Pankratz|first=Howard|title=Alamo Drafthouse in Littleton will screen 'The Interview' starting Christmas|url=http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|accessdate=December 23, 2014|work=The Denver Post|date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223221307/http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27194948/alamo-drafthouse-raises-flag-freedom-promises-show-interview|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony released ''The Interview'' for rental or purchase in the United States through the [[Streaming media|streaming]] services [[Google Play]], [[Xbox Video]], and [[YouTube]] on December 24, 2014. It was also available for a limited time on SeeTheInterview.com, a website operated by the [[stealth startup]] Kernel.com, which Sony previously worked with to market ''[[The Fifth Wave (film)|The Fifth Wave]]''.<ref name=\"variety-kernel\">{{cite web|title=What is Kernel? The Stealth Startup Sony Tapped to Stream 'The Interview' (Exclusive)|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|website=Variety|accessdate=December 30, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230054245/http://variety.com/2014/digital/news/what-is-kernel-the-stealth-startup-sony-tapped-to-stream-the-interview-exclusive-1201386944/|archivedate=December 30, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Within hours, ''The Interview'' spread to [[file sharing]] websites after a security hole allowed people to download rather than stream the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|title=Oops: people are downloading and keeping Sony's rental for The Interview|work=The Verge|accessdate=December 26, 2014|date=December 24, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226080153/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/24/7448253/sonys-the-interview-site-accidentally-let-anyone-download|archivedate=December 26, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[TorrentFreak]] estimated that ''The Interview'' had been downloaded illegally via [[BitTorrent|torrents]] at least 1.5 million times in just two days.<ref name=\"tf-theinterview\">{{cite web|title=The Interview Is A Pirate Hit With 200k Downloads (Updated)|url=http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225|website=[[TorrentFreak]]|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228135544/http://torrentfreak.com/the-interview-is-a-pirate-hit-with-200k-downloads-141225/|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 27, the North Korean [[National Defence Commission]] released a statement accusing President Obama of forcing Sony to distribute the film.<ref name=\"bbc27/12/2014\">{{cite web|title=North Korea berates Obama over The Interview release|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|publisher=BBC News|date=December 27, 2014|accessdate=December 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228161521/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30608179|archivedate=December 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on [[iTunes]] on December 28.<ref name=\"verge-15mill\">{{cite web|title=The Interview makes over $15 million online, beating movie theaters|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|website=The Verge|accessdate=December 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229020127/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/28/7458287/the-interview-opening-weekend-box-office-online-numbers|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the first week of January 2015, Sony announced ''The Interview'' would receive a wide theatrical release in the United Kingdom and Ireland on February 6, but it would not be distributed digitally in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |title=The Interview to receive UK release, Sony confirms |publisher=BBC News |date=January 7, 2015 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110053317/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30707904 |archivedate=January 10, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The film became available for [[Streaming media|streaming]] on [[Netflix]] on January 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|title='The Interview' is on Netflix streaming|website=engadget.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601025257/http://www.engadget.com/2015/01/24/the-interview-netflix/|archivedate=June 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nSony released the film on [[Blu-ray Disc]] and [[DVD]] on February 17, 2015. The home release was packaged as the \"Freedom Edition\", and included 90 minutes of [[deleted scene]]s, behind-the-scenes featurettes, a [[blooper]] reel, [[Audio commentary|feature commentary]] with directors Rogen and Goldberg, and a special episode of ''[[Naked and Afraid]]'' featuring Rogen and Franco.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Chris|title=The Interview is coming to Blu-ray and DVD on February 17th|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|accessdate=January 16, 2015|work=[[The Verge]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116121756/http://www.theverge.com/2015/1/14/7547071/the-interview-coming-to-blu-ray-dvd-february-17|archivedate=January 16, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> {{as of|df=US|2015|07|21|}}, the film had earned over $6.7 million in sales in the U.S.<ref name=\"TheNumbers\">{{cite web | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | title = The Interview (2014) | publisher = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = July 21, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150703215408/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Interview-The#tab=summary | archivedate = July 3, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office and online rentals===\n''The Interview'' opened to a limited release in the United States on December 25, 2014, across 331 theaters<ref>{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | title = 'The Interview' Release: 331 Theaters Aboard For Christmas Day | first1 = Lisa | last1 = de Moraes | first2 = Nellie | last2 = Andreeva | publisher = Deadline.com | date = December 24, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226225615/http://deadline.com/2014/12/interview-christmas-release-theaters-deadline-looms-1201334671/ | archivedate = December 26, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and earned over $1 million on its opening day. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the opening gross \"an impressive launch for a title playing in only about 300 independent theaters in the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | title = Box Office: 'The Interview' Earns $1 Million on Christmas; 'Unbroken,' 'Into the Woods' Surging to $40M | first = Dave | last = McNarry | work = Variety | date = December 26, 2014 | accessdate = December 27, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141227125400/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-the-interview-earns-nearly-1-million-on-christmas-unbroken-into-the-woods-surging-to-40m-1201387451/ | archivedate = December 27, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It went on to earn over $1.8 million in its opening weekend, and by the end of its run on January 25, 2015, had grossed $6.1 million at the box office.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3987&p=.htm | title = Weekend Report (cont.): Huge Limited Debuts for 'American Sniper,' 'Selma' | first = Ray | last = Subers | publisher = Box Office Mojo | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141229090238/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3987&p=.htm | archivedate = December 29, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWithin four days of its online release on December 24, 2014, ''The Interview'' earned over $15 million through online rentals and purchases. It became Sony Pictures' highest-grossing online release, outselling ''[[Arbitrage (film)|Arbitrage]]'' ($14 million), ''[[Bachelorette (film)|Bachelorette]]'' ($8.2 million), and ''[[Snowpiercer]]'' ($7 million).<ref name=\"VOD\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | title = Sony: 'The Interview' Has Made Over $15 Million Online | first = Brent | last = Lang | work = Variety | date = December 28, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141229012755/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/sony-the-interview-has-made-over-15-million-online-1201388557/ | archivedate = December 29, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> It is the top-selling [[Google Play]] and [[YouTube]] film of 2014.<ref>[http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ The Year's top-selling movie on YouTube, Google Play] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231195212/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/12/30/the-interview-google-play-youtube/ |date=December 31, 2014 }}. ''Entertainment Weekly''. Retrieved December 31, 2014.</ref> By January 20, 2015, the film had earned more than $40 million from online sales and rentals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title='The Interview' Makes $40 Million Online and On-Demand|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|accessdate=January 20, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20180116143833/https://variety.com/2015/film/news/the-interview-makes-40-million-online-and-on-demand-1201409731/|archivedate=January 16, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSony expected ''The Interview'' to break even through video-on-demand sales and saving millions of dollars on marketing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Faughdner|first1=Ryan|title=Sony's 'The Interview' to get 'freedom edition' home video release|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|accessdate=January 17, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 14, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117094529/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-sonys-interview-freedom-edition-20150114-story.html|archivedate=January 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[National Association of Theater Owners]] contended that Sony would lose at least $30 million due to poor box office performance.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | title = 'The Interview' Lost Sony $30 Million, Says Theater Group | first = Pamela | last = McClintock | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date = January 16, 2015 | accessdate = January 17, 2015 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150120044501/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/interview-lost-sony-30-million-764366 | archivedate = January 20, 2015 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a 51% approval rating, based on 141 reviews, with an average rating of 5.6/10. The site's consensus reads: \"Unfortunately overshadowed by controversy (and under-screened as a result), ''The Interview''{{'}}s screenplay offers middling laughs bolstered by its two likable leads.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|title=The Interview (2014)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141222025822/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_interview_2014/|archivedate=December 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 52 out of 100, based on 33 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|title=The Interview|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 18, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209073010/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-interview|archivedate=February 9, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[IGN]]'s Roth Cornet wrote that \"though it's unlikely to stand out as one of the shrewdest political satires of its time, [it] is a clever, unrestrained and\u2014most importantly\u2014sidesplitting parody that pokes fun at both a vapid media and one of the world's most dangerous dictators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/12/the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=IGN.com}}</ref> Edward Douglas of [[CraveOnline|ComingSoon.net]] said the film was \"hilarious, but it will probably get us nuked.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|title=The Interview Review|publisher=ComingSoon.net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229175043/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/391477-the-interview-review/slide/1|archivedate=December 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jordan Hoffman of ''The Guardian'' gave the film three out of five stars and wrote that \"if this unessential but agreeable movie really triggered an international response, this is life reflecting art in a major way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|title = The Interview review: stoned, anally fixated \u2013 and funny|date = December 12, 2014|accessdate = December 28, 2014|work = The Guardian|last = Hoffman|first = Jordan|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226005452/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/12/the-interview-review-stoned-anally-fixated-funny|archivedate = December 26, 2014|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nScott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' panned the film as \"cinematic [[waterboarding]]\" and \"about as funny as a communist food shortage, and just as protracted\", but praised the performances of Randall Park and Diana Bang.<ref name=ScottFoundasVariety>{{cite web|last=Foundas|first=Scott|title=Film Review: 'The Interview'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225093148/http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-the-interview-1201376293/|archivedate=December 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' also praised Park and Bang, but wrote that \"after seeing ''The Interview'' and the ruckus its mere existence has caused, the only sensible reaction is amazement at the huge disconnect between the innocuousness of the film and the viciousness of the response.\"<ref name=\"hale\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|title=Memo to Kim Jong-un: Dying Is Easy, Comedy Is Hard|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220053144/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/20/arts/the-disconnect-of-the-interview.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&smid=tw-nytmovies&_r=0|archivedate=December 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Political response===\nIn the wake of the Sony Pictures Entertainment hack, leaks revealed e-mails between Sony Pictures Entertainment CEO Michael Lynton and [[RAND Corporation]] defense analyst Bruce Bennett from June 2014. Bennett advised against toning down ''The Interview''{{-'}}s graphic Jong-un death scene, in the hope that it would \"start some real thinking in South Korea and, I believe, in the North once the DVD leaks into the North\". Bennett expressed his view that \"the only resolution I can see to the North Korean nuclear and other threats is for the North Korean government to eventually go away\", which he felt would be likeliest to occur following an assassination of Kim. Lynton replied that a senior figure in the [[United States Department of State]] agreed. Bennett responded that the office of [[Robert R. King]], U.S. Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, had determined that the North Korean statements had been \"typical North Korean bullying, likely without follow-up\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive: Sony Emails Say State Department Blessed Kim Jong-Un Assassination in 'The Interview'|first=William|last=Boot|work=The Daily Beast|date=December 17, 2014|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217180144/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/17/exclusive-sony-emails-allege-u-s-govt-official-ok-d-controversial-ending-to-the-interview.html|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[CNN]], Bennett said Lynton sits on the board of trustees of the RAND Corporation, which had asked Bennett to talk to Lynton and give his opinion on the film.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |title=Expert on N. Korea on 'The Interview' |date=December 19, 2014 |publisher=CNN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223202708/http://www.cnn.com/video/data/2.0/video/bestoftv/2014/12/19/north-korea-expert-on-sony-hacking.cnn.html |archivedate=December 23, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Bennett felt ''The Interview'' was \"coarse\" and \"over the top\", but that \"the depiction of Kim Jong-un was a picture that needed to get into North Korea. There are a lot of people in prison camps in North Korea who need to take advantage of a change of thinking in the north.\" Bennett felt that if the DVD were smuggled into the country it might have an effect \"over time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|title='The Interview' Release Would Have Damaged Kim Jong Un Internally, Says Rand Expert Who Saw Movie At Sony's Request|date=December 19, 2014|work=Yahoo Movies UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223211521/https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/interview-release-damaged-kim-jong-234915292.html?.tsrc=samsungwn|archivedate=December 23, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bennett contacted the Special Envoy for North Korean Human Rights Issues, a personal friend of his, who \"took the standard government approach: we don't tell industry what to do\".<ref name=\"cnn.com\" /> [[Jen Psaki]], a spokesperson for the United States Department of State, confirmed that [[Daniel R. Russel]], the U.S. [[Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs]], had spoken to Sony executives; she reiterated that \"entertainers are free to make movies of their choosing, and we are not involved in that\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2014/12/235370.htm#DEPARTMENT|title=Daily Press Briefing - December 17, 2014|work=U.S. Department of State|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn [[Greece]], in April 2017, the film's opening scene, depicting a young girl reciting a poem with hate speech, was mistakenly broadcast in the news bulletin of [[Alpha TV]] and the [[news program]] ''Live News'' on [[Open TV|Epsilon TV]], as a real-life provocative event against the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepressproject.gr/article/110363/O-Euaggelatos-parousiazei-skini-satirikis-tainias-gia-ti-BKorea-os-pragmatiki-video|title=\u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 Alpha \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c3\u03ba\u03b7\u03bd\u03ae \u03ba\u03c9\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392.\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1 \u03c9\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae|trans-title=Evangelatos and Alpha present scene of a comedy film about North Korea as a real-life event|language=Greek|website=The Press Project|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref> In response to the backlash on various [[online newspaper]]s, Antonis Sroiter and Nikos Evangelatos, the hosts of the said programs, apologized in posts they made on their social accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topontiki.gr/article/217430/o-nikos-eyaggelatos-zita-syggnomi-gia-tin-gkafa-kaname-lathos|title=\u039f \u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b6\u03b7\u03c4\u03ac \u03c3\u03c5\u03b3\u03b3\u03bd\u03ce\u03bc\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b3\u03ba\u03ac\u03c6\u03b1: \u039a\u03ac\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5 \u03bb\u03ac\u03b8\u03bf\u03c2|trans-title=Nikos Evangelatos apologizes for the blunder: We made a mistake|language=Greek|website=[[To Pontiki]]|date=2017-04-21|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eleftherostypos.gr/perierga/94235-i-apologia-sroiter-gia-to-reportaz-me-to-koritsaki-apo-ti-boreia-korea/|title=\u0397\u2026 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03b1 \u03a3\u03c1\u03cc\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c1\u03b5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03ac\u03b6 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03ba\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1|trans-title=Sroiter's... apology for the reportage with the girl from North Korea|language=Greek|website=[[Eleftheros Typos]]|date=2017-04-22|accessdate=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Freedom of speech|North Korea}}\n* [[Assassinations in fiction]]\n* [[List of films set in or about North Korea]]\n* ''[[Team America: World Police]]'', another comedy film satirizing North Korea\n* ''[[The Dictator (2012 film)|The Dictator]]'', a comedy film satirizing [[Middle East|Middle Eastern]] dictators\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.seetheinterview.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2788710|The Interview}}\n* {{mojo title|interview2014|The Interview}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_interview_2014|The Interview}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-interview|The Interview}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interview, The (2014 film)}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2014 controversies]]\n[[Category:2010s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy films]] \n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s satirical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]] \n[[Category:American political comedy films]]\n[[Category:American political satire films]]\n[[Category:Fiction about assassinations]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Point Grey Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Kim Jong-un]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Events relating to freedom of expression]]\n[[Category:Korean-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Henry Jackman]]\n[[Category:Films about assassinations]]\n[[Category:Films about the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Evan Goldberg]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Seth Rogen]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n[[Category:Films set in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films set in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:North Korea\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Self-censorship]]\n[[Category:Works banned in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "73.194.248.221", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBox office and online rentals)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Interview"}
{"title_page": "Diljott", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Diljott\n| image              = Diljottdiljott.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Diljott\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| occupation         = Actress, singer, philanthropist\n| nationality        = Indian\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| height             = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| education          = Masters in Human Rights (University Gold Medalist), <br /> Bachelors in Psychology Honors (University Gold Medalist),<br /> Post Graduate Course in NGO Management\n}}\n\n'''Diljott''' is an Indian film actress, singer and a philanthropist. She won attention for her lead roles in films like ''Khatre Da Ghuggu'',<ref>{{cite news|title= Up and About Jordan Sandhu and Diljott |url= https://epaper.tribuneindia.com/c/48063559 |newspaper= The Tribune|date= 17 January 2020|accessdate= 18 January 2020}}</ref> [[Teshan (film)|''Teshan'']], ''[[Yaar Annmulle]] 2'', and [[5 Weddings|''5 Weddings'']]. Her released singles include \"Just Love You,\"<ref>{{cite news|title= Counting Her Blessings |url=http://epaper.dailypostindia.com//index.php?mod=1&pgnum=4&edcode=72&pagedate=2018-08-13&type=|date= 13 August 2018|accessdate= 13 August 2018}}</ref> \"Tere Rang,\" \"Akh Mataka\" and \"Maa Meri.\"\n\n== Early life ==\nDiljott was born to a Punjabi family of academicians. She attended Delhi Public School at Chandigarh and later earned her master's degree in Human Rights and Duties from [[Panjab University]], Chandigarh. She topped in the university and was honored with a University Gold Medal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/chandigarh/education/national-student-symposium/134202.html|title=Honor for a Student|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> Diljott was also a University Gold medalist for standing first in the University in Graduation, Bachelor of Arts (Majors in Psychology), Panjab University, Chandigarh.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://punjabimania.com/teshan-actress-diljott-is-a-beauty-with-brains/|title=Actress Diljott is a Beauty with Brains|date=17 September 2016|newspaper=Punjabi Mania|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> Twice being a University Gold Medalist, she did her post graduate course in NGO Management at the Amity Institute of NGO Management and completed a Project Cycle Management Course from NGO Management School at Geneva, Switzerland. Additionally, she has a Certificate Course in Computer and Information Technology.\n\nShe is active in sports<ref>{{cite news|url=http://epaper.tribuneindia.com/1766179/Life+Style-(Chd)/LS-07-August-2018#page/4/1|title=Diet is not a part of my Vocab|date=7 August 2018|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> and believes in a fit and a healthy lifestyle.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://epaper.tribuneindia.com/937662/Life-Style/LS_16_September_2016?show=touch#page/4/1|title=Eat Whatever, but make it small|date=16 September 2016|newspaper=The Tribune Lifestyle|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nDiljott is a trained actor from a Mumbai acting institute and is a [[Kathak]], western, and folk dancer. After working with photographer Dabboo Ratanani, she featured in advertisements for clothing brands and magazine covers including Hindustan Petroleum Corporation Limited, Larsen and Toubro. \n\nShe is fluent in English, [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and [[Hindi]] and works in [[Bollywood]] and Punjabi cinema as an actress.<ref>{{cite news|title= Plans for Pollywood |url= https://epaper.tribuneindia.com/c/35371424 |date= 1 January 2019|accessdate= 1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe featured in the Punjabi song \"Patiala Peg\" opposite Diljit Dosanjh,<ref>{{cite news|title= Emerging Punjabi Actress |url= http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31973&articlexml=EMERGING-PUNJABI-SIRENS-29102016107021|date= 29 October 2016|accessdate= 31 October 2016}}</ref> which became a hit track.<ref>{{cite news|title=Diljott: Meet The  \u2018Patiala Peg\u2019 Girl|url=http://www.darpanmagazine.com/magazine/spotlight/diljott-meet-the-patiala-peg-girl/|newspaper=Darpan Magazine|date=26 November 2015|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> Diljott's films as a lead actress in ''Teshan''<ref>{{cite news|title= Film Teshan|url=https://dailypost.in/news/entertainment/set-big-screen-debut/|newspaper= Daily Post|date= 24 September 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> (2016)<ref>{{cite news|title= Teshan 2016 Movie|url=http://www.unp.me/f185/teshan-2016-happy-raikoti-and-diljott-movie-295258/|newspaper= Punjabi Internet Portal|date= 25 August 2016|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= All set for the Big Screen|url=http://epaper.dailypostindia.com/epapermain.aspx?queryed=9&eddate=2016-09-23|newspaper= Daily Post|date= 23 September 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref> and ''Yaar Annmulle 2'' (2017)<ref>{{cite news|title= Film Yaar Annmulle 2 |url= http://epaper.tribuneindia.com/1010685/Life-Style/LS_23_November_2016#page/3/1|date= 23 November 2016|accessdate= 23 November 2016}}</ref> were hits.<ref>{{cite news|title= Film Teshan Movie Review|url= http://www.pollywoodnews.com/teshan-movie-review/|newspaper= Pollywood News|date= 24 September 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> She starred as the lead in the film ''Idiot Boys'' (2014). She appeared Hollywood film ''5 Weddings'' (2018).<ref>{{cite news|title= Diljott in Hollywood film '5 Weddings'|url= http://www.babushahi.com/full-news.php?id=52612|date= 3 December 2016|accessdate= 3 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Hollywood film '5 Weddings'|url=http://m.bollywoodtadka.in/entertainment/news/hollywood-movie-shoot-in-mohali--546532|date= 3 December 2016|accessdate= 3 December 2016}}</ref> She starred in ''Khatre Da Ghuggu'' (2020). \n\nHer single \"Tere Rang\" (2017).<ref>{{cite news|title= Saluting the power of Woman|url=http://epaper.tribuneindia.com/1080803/Life-Style/LS_24_January_2017#page/4/1|newspaper=The Tribune|date= 24 January 2017|accessdate= 24 January 2017}}</ref> This song was used as a playback song for ''5 Weddings''.<ref>{{cite news|title= Song 'Tere Rang' just got picked up by a Hollywood Movie|url= https://www.ghaintpunjab.com/GhaintPunjab/Article/10326/this-punjabi-actress-track-justgot-picked-up-by-a-hollywood-movie |newspaper= Ghaint Punjab |date= 23 February 2018|accessdate= 23 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Diljott's Punjabi Song featuring in Hollywood production|url=http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31973&articlexml=PU-ALUMNUS-DILJOTTS-PUNJABI-SONG-IS-FEATURING-IN-28012017106008|newspaper=The Times of India|date= 28 January 2017|accessdate= 29 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Raj Kundra's maiden Punjabi production 'Nanak'|url=http://www.ghaintpunjab.com/GhaintPunjab/Article/6739/raj-kundras-maiden-punjabi-production-is-titled-nanak|newspaper=Ghaint Punjab|date= 21 June 2016|accessdate= 22 June 2016}}</ref> Another single was \"Akh Mataka\" (2017).<ref>{{cite news|title= Diljott's new single track song 'Akh Mataka'|url=https://www.gabruu.com/vekho-diljott-de-aaun-vale-gane-akh-mataka-de-behind-the-camera-scenes/|newspaper=Gabruu|date= 26 June 2017|accessdate= 27 June 2017}}</ref> Dilijott performed at the 2016 Virasat International Punjabi Film Festival and Awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=No one formula to success:Diljott|url=http://m.epaper.bhaskar.com/magazine/navrang-punjab/450/04082017/mpcg/2/|newspaper=Dainik Bhaskar|date= 3 August 2017|accessdate= 4 August 2017}}</ref> Her song \"Maa Meri\" (2017) is an ode to mothers. \"Just Love You\" (2018) was a romantic song.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Film\n!scope=\"col\"| Language\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unso